{"title_page": "Martin Lister", "text_new": "{{For|his father, the English politician|Martin Lister (MP)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = \n| image             = Martin-Lister.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1639|04|12}}\n| birth_place       = Radcliffe, [[Buckinghamshire]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1712|02|02|1639|04|12}} \n| death_place       = [[Epsom]], Surrey\n| resting_place     = Clapham Church\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = British\n| nationality       = \n| fields            = Physician and naturalist\n| workplaces        = \n| alma_mater        = St John's, Cambridge\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = \n| children          = \n}}\n'''Martin Lister''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (12 April 1639 \u2013 2 February 1712) was an English [[natural history|naturalist]] and physician. His daughters [[Anne Lister (illustrator)|Anne Lister]] and [[Susanna Lister (illustrator)|Susanna Lister]] were two of his illustrators and engravers.<ref name=sisters>\nJ. D. Woodley, \u2018Lister , Susanna (bap. 1670, d. 1738)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, Jan 2008 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/58454, accessed 10 April 2017]</ref>\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Cornelius Johnson - Portrait of Susanna Temple, Later Lady Lister - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|Lister's mother, Susan (or Susanna) Temple, later Lady Lister (1620), by [[Cornelius Johnson (artist)|Cornelius Johnson]].]]Lister was born at Radcliffe, near [[Buckingham]], the son of [[Martin Lister (MP)|Sir Martin Lister]] MP for Brackley in the [[Long Parliament]] and his wife Susan Temple daughter of [[Alexander Temple|Sir Alexander Temple]]. Lister was connected to a number of well known individuals. He was the nephew of both [[James Temple]], the regicide and also of Sir Matthew Lister, physician to [[Anne of Denmark|Anne]], queen of [[James I of England|James I]], and to [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]. He was also the uncle of [[Sarah Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough]] who corresponded with him throughout her life.<ref>{{cite book|first=Anna Marie|last=Roos|title=Web of Nature: Martin Lister (1639\u20131712), the First Arachnologist|page=49|publisher=Brill Academic Publishers|year=2011|isbn=9789004207035}}</ref>\n\nLister was educated at [[Melton Mowbray]], Leicestershire under Mr Barwick and matriculated at [[St John's College, Cambridge]] in 1658. He graduated in 1658/9, and was elected a fellow in 1660.<ref name=Venn>{{acad|id=LSTR655M|name=Lister, Martin}}</ref> In 1668 he travelled to France to study as a physician and settled at [[York]] in 1670 to practice medicine.<ref name=Hutton>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Z0gryhSvy1MC&pg=PA556&lpg=PA556&dq=%22Martin+Lister%22+physician&source=bl&ots=PlUW91kG5e&sig=vrkIAbl-aa976hyPytngLSoVwEU&hl=en&ei=tO8pTaunNYyKhQey8dG3Dg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=%22Martin%20Lister%22%20physician&f=false Royal Society (Great Britain), Charles Hutton ''The Philosophical transactions of the Royal Society of London, Volume 1'']</ref> He became [[List of Fellows of the Royal Society J,K,L|Fellow of the Royal Society]] on 2 November 1671. He practised medicine at York until 1683, when he moved to London. In 1684 he received the degree of M.D. at [[university of Oxford|Oxford]] on the recommendation of the Chancellor.<ref name=Hutton/> In 1687 became [[Royal College of Physicians|F.R.C.P.]].\n\nLister bought Carlton Hall in Craven in the West Riding of Yorkshire.  He attended the Earl of Portland when he was ambassador to France in 1698.\n\nHe was physician to Queen Anne from 1709 until his death.<ref name=Hutton/> He died at [[Epsom]] at the age of 72 and was buried at Clapham Church.<ref name=Venn/>\n\nLister was a prolific correspondent. More than 2,000 letters written by and to him survive in the [[Bodleian Library]], Oxford and other repositories. They are to and from a variety of people including family, friends and other scientists. Abstracts of these letters have been published on line.<ref>[http://emlo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/profile/person/96eb67df-642f-4919-8c0b-6247209caed4 Early Modern Letters Online]</ref>\n\n==Memorial inscription==\nThe memorial inscription in Clapham church is now lost. It read:\n\nNear this place is buried the body of\n\nMARTIN LISTER,\n\nDoctor of Physick, a Member of the\n\nRoyal Society, and one of\n\nQueen Ann\u2019s Physicians,\n\nwho departed this life,\n\nthe second day of\n\nFebruary 1711\u201312.<ref>[http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/2762 Royal College of Physicians]</ref>\n\n==Scientific work==\nLister contributed numerous articles on natural history, medicine and antiquities to the ''[[Philosophical Transactions]]''. He was the first arachnologist and conchologist, and provided an unprecedented picture of a seventeenth-century virtuoso. Lister is recognized for his discovery of [[Ballooning (spider)|ballooning spider]]s and as the father of [[conchology]], but it is less well known that he invented the [[histogram]], provided Newton with alloys, and donated the first significant natural history collections to the Ashmolean Museum. Just as Lister was the first to make a systematic study of spiders and their webs, this biography is the first to analyze the significant webs of knowledge, patronage, and familial and gender relationships that governed his life as a scientist and physician. His principal works were ''Historiae animalium Angliae tres tractatus'' (1678) which was the first organised, systematic publication on shells;<ref>[http://lhldigital.lindahall.org/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=/nat_hist&CISOPTR=2392&REC=4 Historiae Conchyliorum, Vol. 1 and 2 (1685)] \u2013 digital facsimile, Linda Hall Library]</ref> ''Historiae Conchyliorum'' (1685 1692), and ''Conchyliorum Bivalvium'' (1696). As a [[conch]]ologist he was held in high esteem, but while he recognised the similarity of [[fossil]] [[mollusc]]a to living forms, he regarded them as inorganic imitations produced in the rocks. Lister employed his daughters from an early age. His daughters, [[Anne Lister (illustrator)|Anne Lister]], and [[Susanna Lister]] were both credited as his illustrators and engravers.<ref name=sisters/>\n\nIn 1683 he communicated to the [[Royal Society]] (1684<ref>''Lister M.'' An ingenious proposal for a new sort of maps of countries, together with tables of sands and clays, such chiefly as are found in the north parts of England, drawn up about 10 years since, and delivered to the Royal Society Mar. 12. 1683. by the Learned Martin Lister M.D. In [http://rstl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/14/155-166/739 Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029051814/http://rstl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/14/155-166/739 |date=29 October 2015 }}. 1684. Vol. 14. P. 739-746.</ref>), an ingenious proposal for a new sort of maps of countries; together with tables of sands and clays, such as are chiefly found in the north parts of England. In this essay he suggested the preparation of a soil or mineral map of the country, and thereby is justly credited with being the first to realise the importance of a geological survey.\n\n[[Charles Lyell]] speaks of Lister in his ''[[Principles of Geology]]'' as follows: \n<blockquote>\n[[w:Robert Plot|Dr. Plot]], in his 'Natural History of Oxfordshire.' (1677) attributed to a 'plastic virtue latent in the earth' the origin of fossil shells and fishes; and Lister, to his accurate account of British shells, in 1678, added the fossil species, under the appellation of ''turbinated and bivalve stones''. 'Either,' said he, 'these were terriginous, or if otherwise, the animals they so exactly represent ''have become extinct''. This writer appears to have been the first who was aware of the continuity over large districts of the principal groups of strata in the British series, and who proposed the construction of regular geological maps.<ref>[[wikiquote:Charles Lyell|Charles Lyell]], ''[https://archive.org/details/principlesgeolo01unkngoog Principles of Geology]'', 1832, p.35</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nHe was a benefactor of the [[Ashmolean Museum]] in Oxford.<ref name=Hutton/> The ridge [[Dorsa Lister]] in the [[Mare Serenitatis|Sea of Serenity]] on the Moon was named after him.\n\n==Publications==\n[[File:Lister Martin conchs 1770.png|thumb|upright|right|Plate from ''Historiae Conchyliorum'' (1691).]]\n* ''Histories Animalium Angliae tres tractatus, &ct,, l678.\n* ''Goedartii Historia Insectorum cum notis, 1682.\n* ''De Fontibus medicinalibus Angliae,,, l682.\n* ''Historiae Conchyliorum'', 1685\n* ''Exercitatio Anatomica, in qua de Cochlcis agitur, 1694.\n* ''Cochlearum ct Linacum exercitatio Anatomica,,, 1695.\n* ''Conchyliorum bivalvium utriusque aquae exercitatio Anatomica tertia, 1696.\n* ''Exercitationes Medicinales, &tc,,. 1697.\n* ''Journey to Paris'', c 1699\n\n==See also==\n*[[Historiae animalium (Gesner)|Historiae animalium]], by [[Conrad Gesner]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*''Dr. Martin Lister: A bibliography'' by Geoffrey Keynes. (Includes illustrations by Lister's wife and daughter). Published by St Paul's Bibliographies (UK) with an {{ISBN|0-906795-04-4}}\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Lister, Martin}}\n\n==External links==\n*Lister, Martin (1678) [http://lhldigital.lindahall.org/cdm/ref/collection/nat_hist/id/22115 ''Histori\u00e6 Animalium Angli\u00e6''] - digital facsimile at the [[Linda Hall Library]]\n*Lister, Martin (1685) [http://lhldigital.lindahall.org/cdm/ref/collection/nat_hist/id/2392 ''Historae conchyliorum.../ Susanna et Anna Lister figuras pin, two vol.''] - digital facsimile from the [[Linda Hall Library]]\n*[http://emlo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/blog/?catalogue=martin-lister The Correspondence of Martin Lister] in [http://emlo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/home EMLO]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lister, Martin}}\n[[Category:1639 births]]\n[[Category:1712 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:18th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:English naturalists]]\n[[Category:English geologists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:People from Radcliffe, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|his father, the English politician|Martin Lister (MP)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = \n| image             = Martin-Lister.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|df=yes|1639|04|12}}\n| birth_place       = Radcliffe, [[Buckinghamshire]]\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1712|02|02|1639|04|12}} \n| death_place       = [[Epsom]], Surrey\n| resting_place     = Clapham Church\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = British\n| nationality       = \n| fields            = Physician and naturalist\n| workplaces        = \n| alma_mater        = St John's, Cambridge\n| thesis_title      = \n| thesis_url        = \n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| footnotes         = \n| spouse            = \n| children          = \n}}\n'''Martin Lister''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (12 April 1639 \u2013 2 February 1712) was an English [[natural history|naturalist]] and physician. His daughters [[Anne Lister (illustrator)|Anne Lister]] and [[Susanna Lister (illustrator)|Susanna Lister]] were two of his illustrators and engravers.<ref name=sisters>\nJ. D. Woodley, \u2018Lister , Susanna (bap. 1670, d. 1738)\u2019, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, Jan 2008 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/58454, accessed 10 April 2017]</ref>\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Cornelius Johnson - Portrait of Susanna Temple, Later Lady Lister - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|Lister's mother, Susan (or Susanna) Temple, later Lady Lister (1620), by [[Cornelius Johnson (artist)|Cornelius Johnson]].]]Lister was born at Radcliffe, near [[Buckingham]], the son of [[Martin Lister (MP)|Sir Martin Lister]] MP for Brackley in the [[Long Parliament]] and his wife Susan Temple daughter of [[Alexander Temple|Sir Alexander Temple]]. Lister was connected to a number of well known individuals. He was the nephew of both [[James Temple]], the regicide and also of Sir Matthew Lister, physician to [[Anne of Denmark|Anne]], queen of [[James I of England|James I]], and to [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]. He was also the uncle of [[Sarah Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough]] who corresponded with him throughout her life.<ref>{{cite book|first=Anna Marie|last=Roos|title=Web of Nature: Martin Lister (1639\u20131712), the First Arachnologist|page=49|publisher=Brill Academic Publishers|year=2011|isbn=9789004207035}}</ref>\n\nLister was educated at [[Melton Mowbray]], Leicestershire under Mr Barwick and matriculated at [[St John's College, Cambridge]] in 1658. He graduated in 1658/9, and was elected a fellow in 1660.<ref name=Venn>{{acad|id=LSTR655M|name=Lister, Martin}}</ref> In 1668 he travelled to France to study as a physician and settled at [[York]] in 1670 to practice medicine.<ref name=Hutton>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Z0gryhSvy1MC&pg=PA556&lpg=PA556&dq=%22Martin+Lister%22+physician&source=bl&ots=PlUW91kG5e&sig=vrkIAbl-aa976hyPytngLSoVwEU&hl=en&ei=tO8pTaunNYyKhQey8dG3Dg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=%22Martin%20Lister%22%20physician&f=false Royal Society (Great Britain), Charles Hutton ''The Philosophical transactions of the Royal Society of London, Volume 1'']</ref> He became [[List of Fellows of the Royal Society J,K,L|Fellow of the Royal Society]] on 2 November 1671. He practised medicine at York until 1683, when he moved to London. In 1684 he received the degree of M.D. at [[university of Oxford|Oxford]] on the recommendation of the Chancellor.<ref name=Hutton/> In 1687 became [[Royal College of Physicians|F.R.C.P.]].\n\nLister bought Carlton Hall in Craven in the West Riding of Yorkshire.  He attended the Earl of Portland when he was ambassador to France in 1698.\n\nHe was physician to Queen Anne from 1709 until his death.<ref name=Hutton/> He died at [[Epsom]] at the age of 72 and was buried at Clapham Church.<ref name=Venn/>\n\nLister was a prolific correspondent. More than 2,000 letters written by and to him survive in the [[Bodleian Library]], Oxford and other repositories. They are to and from a variety of people including family, friends and other scientists. Abstracts of these letters have been published on line.<ref>[http://emlo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/profile/person/96eb67df-642f-4919-8c0b-6247209caed4 Early Modern Letters Online]</ref>\n\n==Memorial inscription==\nThe memorial inscription in Clapham church is now lost. It read:\n\nNear this place is buried the body of\n\nMARTIN LISTER,\n\nDoctor of Physick, a Member of the\n\nRoyal Society, and one of\n\nQueen Ann\u2019s Physicians,\n\nwho departed this life,\n\nthe second day of\n\nFebruary 1711\u201312.<ref>[http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/2762 Royal College of Physicians]</ref>\n\n==Scientific work==\nLister contributed numerous articles on natural history, medicine and antiquities to the ''[[Philosophical Transactions]]''. He was the first arachnologist and conchologist, and provided an unprecedented picture of a seventeenth-century virtuoso. Lister is recognized for his discovery of [[Ballooning (spider)|ballooning spider]]s and as the father of [[conchology]], but it is less well known that he invented the [[histogram]], provided Newton with alloys, and donated the first significant natural history collections to the Ashmolean Museum. Just as Lister was the first to make a systematic study of spiders and their webs, this biography is the first to analyze the significant webs of knowledge, patronage, and familial and gender relationships that governed his life as a scientist and physician. His principal works were ''Historiae animalium Angliae tres tractatus'' (1678) which was the first organised, systematic publication on shells;<ref>[http://lhldigital.lindahall.org/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=/nat_hist&CISOPTR=2392&REC=4 Historiae Conchyliorum, Vol. 1 and 2 (1685)] \u2013 digital facsimile, Linda Hall Library]</ref> ''Historiae Conchyliorum'' (1685 1692), and ''Conchyliorum Bivalvium'' (1696). As a [[conch]]ologist he was held in high esteem, but while he recognised the similarity of [[fossil]] [[mollusc]]a to living forms, he regarded them as inorganic imitations produced in the rocks. Lister employed his daughters from an early age. His daughters, [[Anne Lister (illustrator)|Anne Lister]], and [[Susanna Lister (illustrator)|Susanna Lister]] were both credited as his illustrators and engravers.<ref name=sisters/>\n\nIn 1683 he communicated to the [[Royal Society]] (1684<ref>''Lister M.'' An ingenious proposal for a new sort of maps of countries, together with tables of sands and clays, such chiefly as are found in the north parts of England, drawn up about 10 years since, and delivered to the Royal Society Mar. 12. 1683. by the Learned Martin Lister M.D. In [http://rstl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/14/155-166/739 Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029051814/http://rstl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/14/155-166/739 |date=29 October 2015 }}. 1684. Vol. 14. P. 739-746.</ref>), an ingenious proposal for a new sort of maps of countries; together with tables of sands and clays, such as are chiefly found in the north parts of England. In this essay he suggested the preparation of a soil or mineral map of the country, and thereby is justly credited with being the first to realise the importance of a geological survey.\n\n[[Charles Lyell]] speaks of Lister in his ''[[Principles of Geology]]'' as follows: \n<blockquote>\n[[w:Robert Plot|Dr. Plot]], in his 'Natural History of Oxfordshire.' (1677) attributed to a 'plastic virtue latent in the earth' the origin of fossil shells and fishes; and Lister, to his accurate account of British shells, in 1678, added the fossil species, under the appellation of ''turbinated and bivalve stones''. 'Either,' said he, 'these were terriginous, or if otherwise, the animals they so exactly represent ''have become extinct''. This writer appears to have been the first who was aware of the continuity over large districts of the principal groups of strata in the British series, and who proposed the construction of regular geological maps.<ref>[[wikiquote:Charles Lyell|Charles Lyell]], ''[https://archive.org/details/principlesgeolo01unkngoog Principles of Geology]'', 1832, p.35</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nHe was a benefactor of the [[Ashmolean Museum]] in Oxford.<ref name=Hutton/> The ridge [[Dorsa Lister]] in the [[Mare Serenitatis|Sea of Serenity]] on the Moon was named after him.\n\n==Publications==\n[[File:Lister Martin conchs 1770.png|thumb|upright|right|Plate from ''Historiae Conchyliorum'' (1691).]]\n* ''Histories Animalium Angliae tres tractatus, &ct,, l678.\n* ''Goedartii Historia Insectorum cum notis, 1682.\n* ''De Fontibus medicinalibus Angliae,,, l682.\n* ''Historiae Conchyliorum'', 1685\n* ''Exercitatio Anatomica, in qua de Cochlcis agitur, 1694.\n* ''Cochlearum ct Linacum exercitatio Anatomica,,, 1695.\n* ''Conchyliorum bivalvium utriusque aquae exercitatio Anatomica tertia, 1696.\n* ''Exercitationes Medicinales, &tc,,. 1697.\n* ''Journey to Paris'', c 1699\n\n==See also==\n*[[Historiae animalium (Gesner)|Historiae animalium]], by [[Conrad Gesner]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*''Dr. Martin Lister: A bibliography'' by Geoffrey Keynes. (Includes illustrations by Lister's wife and daughter). Published by St Paul's Bibliographies (UK) with an {{ISBN|0-906795-04-4}}\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Lister, Martin}}\n\n==External links==\n*Lister, Martin (1678) [http://lhldigital.lindahall.org/cdm/ref/collection/nat_hist/id/22115 ''Histori\u00e6 Animalium Angli\u00e6''] - digital facsimile at the [[Linda Hall Library]]\n*Lister, Martin (1685) [http://lhldigital.lindahall.org/cdm/ref/collection/nat_hist/id/2392 ''Historae conchyliorum.../ Susanna et Anna Lister figuras pin, two vol.''] - digital facsimile from the [[Linda Hall Library]]\n*[http://emlo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/blog/?catalogue=martin-lister The Correspondence of Martin Lister] in [http://emlo.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/home EMLO]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lister, Martin}}\n[[Category:1639 births]]\n[[Category:1712 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:18th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:English naturalists]]\n[[Category:English geologists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:People from Radcliffe, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n", "name_user": "Alter Meister", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eScientific work:blue", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Lister"}
{"title_page": "Interstate 5", "text_new": "{{Redirect|I-5||I5 (disambiguation)}}\n{{For|the Wedding Present song|Interstate 5 (song)}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Short description|Interstate along the West Coast of the US}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=USA\n|type=I\n|route=5\n|length_mi=1381.29\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"fhwa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/reports/routefinder/table1.cfm|work=Route Log and Finder List |title= Table 1: Main Routes of the Dwight D. Eisenhower National System Of Interstate and Defense Highways as of December 31, 2013 |date= December 31, 2013 |author= Staff |publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]]|accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref>\n|history=Designated in 1956<br/>Completed in 1979\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=BCN|FH|1}} at the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican border]] at [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro, CA]]\n|junction=<!-- Major junctions ONLY; Only 5-7 most major intersections and cities belong here; please read [[WP:USRD/STDS]] for more info; please do not add any more! -->{{plainlist|1=\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|15}} to [[Interstate 15|I-15]] in [[San Diego|San Diego, CA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|8}} in San Diego, CA\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|10|US|101}} in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, CA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|US|50}} in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento, CA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|80}} in Sacramento, CA\n*{{jct|country=USA|US|20}} in [[Albany, Oregon|Albany, OR]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|84|dab1= Oregon\u2013Utah|US|30}} in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland, OR]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|US|101}} in [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia, WA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|90}} in [[Seattle|Seattle, WA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|US|2}} in [[Everett, Washington|Everett, WA]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{jct|province=BC|BC|99}} at the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canada\u2013US border]] at [[Blaine, Washington|Blaine, WA]]\n|states=[[California]], [[Oregon]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n}}\n'''Interstate 5''' ('''I-5''') is the main north\u2013south [[Interstate Highway System|Interstate Highway]] on the [[West Coast of the United States]], running largely parallel to the [[Pacific coast]] of the contiguous U.S. from [[Mexico]] to [[Canada]]. It travels through the states of [[California]], [[Oregon]], and [[Washington (state)|Washington]], serving several large cities on the U.S. West Coast, including [[San Diego]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], and [[Seattle]]. It is the only continuous Interstate highway to touch both the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican]] and the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian]] borders. Upon crossing the Mexican border at its southern terminus, I-5 continues to [[Tijuana]], Baja California, as [[Mexico Federal Highway 1]] (Fed.&nbsp;1). Upon crossing the Canadian border at its northern terminus, it continues to [[Vancouver]] as [[British Columbia Highway 99]] (BC&nbsp;99).\n\nI-5 was originally created in 1956 as part of the Interstate Highway System, but it was predated by several auto trails and highways built in the early 20th century. The Pacific Highway auto trail was built in the 1910s and 1920s by the states of California, Oregon, and Washington, and was later incorporated into [[U.S. Route 99]] (US&nbsp;99) in 1926. I-5 largely follows the route of US&nbsp;99, with the exception of a portion in the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] of California. The freeway was built in segments between 1956 and 1978, including expressway sections of US&nbsp;99 that were built earlier to bypass various towns along the route.\n\n==Route description==\n{{lengths table|length_ref=<ref name=\"fhwa\" />}}\n|-\n|[[Interstate 5 in California|CA]]\n|{{convert|796.53|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[Interstate 5 in Oregon|OR]]\n|{{convert|308.14|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[Interstate 5 in Washington|WA]]\n|{{convert|276.62|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|Total\n|{{convert|1381.29|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|}\n\n===California===\n[[File:Interstate5newhallpass.JPG|thumb|right|I-5 in the [[Newhall Pass Interchange]] where it intersects with [[Interstate 210 and State Route 210 (California)|I-210]] and [[California State Route 14|State Route 14]] near [[Santa Clarita, California|Santa Clarita]] ]]\n{{main|Interstate 5 in California}}\nThe southernmost point of I-5 is at the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican border]] at the [[San Ysidro Port of Entry]], one of the busiest border crossings in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-005.html |title=Busiest border crossing |publisher=Interstate-guide.com |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2011}}{{unreliable source?|failed=y|date=March 2014}}</ref> Beginning at the border in [[San Ysidro, San Deigeo|San Ysidro]] which is part of the city of [[San Diego]], as the [[John J. Montgomery Freeway]], I-5 goes through the suburbs of [[Chula Vista, California|Chula Vista]] and [[National City, California|National City]] before reaching downtown San Diego. It then parallels the Pacific coastline, going through the northern suburbs of San Diego, bisecting the [[University of California, San Diego]] campus, and passing the I-805 merge (where it becomes the widest Interstate in the United States for a short stretch), before passing through several [[North County (San Diego area)|North County]] coastal suburbs and then through {{convert|18|mi|km}} of [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] Base [[Camp Pendleton, California|Camp Pendleton]] in northern [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]]. Here I-5 is also known as the San Diego Freeway.\n\nAt [[Dana Point, California|Dana Point]], I-5 turns inland and heads due north through [[Mission Viejo, California|Mission Viejo]] to the [[El Toro Y]] interchange in southeastern [[Irvine, California|Irvine]]. I-5 becomes the [[Santa Ana Freeway]] as it runs southeast to northwest, passing through major cities and suburbs in [[Orange County, California|Orange]] and [[Los Angeles County, California|Southern Los Angeles]] counties. Southern Californians often refer to it as \"the 5\" or as the Santa Ana Freeway in the Los Angeles area. From this point, the San Diego Freeway continues northward as I-405.\n\nWhen the freeway reaches the [[East Los Angeles Interchange]] {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} east of downtown [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], I-5 becomes the [[Golden State Freeway]]. The route continues through the [[San Fernando Valley]] and then crosses the [[Newhall Pass]] through the [[Santa Susana Mountains]] into the [[Santa Clarita Valley]]. The interchange with [[California State Route 14|State Route 14]] (SR&nbsp;14) is unusual in that truck traffic is separated into its own lanes for both the mainline of the freeway and the transition ramps to and from SR&nbsp;14. For about a {{convert|5|mi|km|adj=on|spell=in}} stretch between the Santa Clarita Valley and [[Pyramid Lake (Los Angeles County, California)|Pyramid Lake]], the northbound and southbound lanes separate and cross sides, with the southbound lanes running to the east of the northbound ones. At that point, the Golden State Freeway rises sharply to the north through [[Ridge Route#Features|the Grapevine]] to eventually reach the second-highest point of its entire length, the [[Tejon Pass]] (elevation {{convert|4144|ft|m|abbr=on|disp=or}}). Through the [[Tehachapi Mountains]]. [[Path 26]] [[electric power transmission|power lines]] generally follow the freeway along this stretch. The freeway then descends sharply for {{convert|12|mi|km}} at Tejon Pass to around {{convert|1500|ft|m}} at Grapevine near the southernmost point of the [[San Joaquin Valley]], approximately {{convert|30|mi|km}} south of [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]] and {{convert|5|mi|km|abbr=on}} south from where [[California State Route 99|SR&nbsp;99]] splits away from it in [[Wheeler Ridge, California|Wheeler Ridge]].\n\n[[File:I-5 near Shasta.jpg|thumb|left|I-5 south approaching Weed and Mount Shasta]]\n\nFrom SR&nbsp;99 to south of [[Tracy, California|Tracy]], I-5 skirts along the far more remote western edge of the great [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]], and thus here is removed from population centers such as [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]] and [[Fresno, California|Fresno]]; other state highways provide these connections. This part of I-5 is known as the West Side Freeway, and is a major connector between the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] and Southern California. [[Interstate 580 (California)|I-580]] splits from I-5 at a point south of Tracy as the West Side Freeway Scenic Byway, the last stretch of the West Side Freeway\u2014providing a loop-route connection to the San Francisco Bay Area. East of Tracy, I-5 intersects with I-205, another freeway that links I-5 to the Bay Area and passes through Tracy. After passing Tracy, I-5 heads north through [[Stockton, California|Stockton]] and [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] before turning west to [[Woodland, California|Woodland]]. At Woodland, the Interstate heads northwest again towards [[Dunnigan, California|Dunnigan]], where it converges with [[Interstate 505|I-505]].\n\nFrom Dunnigan, I-5 skirts north along the western edge of the [[Sacramento Valley]] to [[Red Bluff, California|Red Bluff]]. I-5 then enters the [[Shasta Cascade]] region, passing through [[Redding, California|Redding]] and [[Shasta Lake]] before climbing up to near the foot of [[Mount Shasta]]. The interstate then travels to [[Weed, California|Weed]] and [[Yreka, California|Yreka]] before reaching the Oregon border.\n\n===Oregon===\n{{main|Interstate 5 in Oregon}}\n[[File:I5inPortlandNight.jpg|right|thumb|I-5 running adjacent to the [[Willamette River]] and passes by the [[Moda Center]], and [[Oregon Convention Center]] in Downtown Portland]]\nAbout {{convert|3|mi|km|spell=in}} north of the California border, the highway crosses {{convert|4310|ft|m}} [[Siskiyou Summit]], the highest point on I-5, and then drops down into the [[Rogue Valley]] through Oregon's southern mountains and towns such as [[Ashland, Oregon|Ashland]], [[Medford, Oregon|Medford]] and [[Grants Pass, Oregon|Grants Pass]]. Turning north across three passes to the Umpqua Valley and through [[Roseburg, Oregon|Roseburg]], the mountains tend to turn into hills, and as it reaches Cottage Grove, the road enters the [[Willamette Valley|Willamette River Valley]]. At [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]] the highway intersects [[Oregon Route 126|I-105]], a short spur route into Downtown [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]]. Some city highways intersect on I-5 in the Eugene Metro. The Interstate then heads almost due north, skirting [[Albany, Oregon|Albany]] and [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]], passing through [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]], and crossing through [[Woodburn, Oregon|Woodburn]]. There were plans to build a spur, called [[Interstate 305 (Oregon)|I-305]], into Salem. I-5 covers {{convert|308|mi|km}} in [[Oregon]].\n\nJust north of Salem, between mile markers 259 and 260 just short of mile marker 260, signs in the median and on both shoulders mark the place where the [[45th parallel north|45th parallel]] crosses I-5. It reads \"45th Parallel half way between the Equator and the North Pole\".\n\nThe highway then tracks a little to the northeast, and [[Interstate 205 (Oregon\u2013Washington)|I-205]] splits off south of the [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] metro area. From here I-5 passes through Tualatin and Tigard along former [[U.S. Route 99W (Oregon)|U.S. Route 99W]] (US&nbsp;99W) before hitting the southern terminus of [[Interstate 405 (Oregon)|I-405]] and the [[Marquam Bridge]]. Also planned was a spur in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] off I-405, called [[Interstate 505 (Oregon)|I-505]], but it was never built and has been removed from city plans. A stub of I-505 exists as a long exit ramp to [[U.S. Route 30|US&nbsp;30]].\n\nAfter crossing the Willamette River on the [[Marquam Bridge]], I-5 has junctions at the western end of [[Interstate 84 in Oregon|I-84]] and the northern end of I-405. It then continues through the northern parts of the city of Portland, and crosses into Washington via the [[Interstate Bridge]].\n\n===Washington===\n{{main|Interstate 5 in Washington}}\n[[File:SeattleI5Skyline.jpg|thumb|right|I-5 passing through downtown Seattle]]\nThe highway continues over the [[Columbia River]] and drops down into the city of [[Vancouver, Washington|Vancouver]]. About {{convert|7|mi|km|spell=in}} into the state, it reaches the northern terminus of [[Interstate 205 (Oregon\u2013Washington)|I-205]], which is on the eastern edge of the Portland\u2013Vancouver metropolitan area. It then tracks north by northwest through [[Woodland, Washington|Woodland]] to [[Kelso, Washington|Kelso]] and [[Longview, Washington|Longview]], at which point it ceases to parallel a large bend of the Columbia River. Continuing north between the [[Willapa Hills]] and the Cascade foothills, the freeway eventually reaches [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia]], where it bends sharply east. The highway passes through the northern end of [[Joint Base Lewis-McChord]] (formerly [[Fort Lewis]] and [[McChord Field|McChord Air Force Base]]) and [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]], where it bends sharply north again to reach [[Seattle]]. The [[Ship Canal Bridge]] carries it over [[Portage Bay]] in Seattle. The freeway continues north out of the Seattle\u2013Tacoma\u2013[[Everett, Washington|Everett]] metro area, crosses the floodplains of three rivers, through the Skagit Valley and the Mount Vernon\u2013Burlington Metropolitan Area to the northern city of [[Bellingham, Washington|Bellingham]], to arrive at the [[Peace Arch]] Canada\u2013US border crossing between [[Blaine, Washington]], and [[Surrey, British Columbia]]. [[British Columbia Highway 99|Highway 99]] continues northwest from the border into [[Vancouver|Vancouver, BC]]. I-5 covers {{convert|277|mi|km}} in Washington.\n\n==History==\n{{imageframe|width=100|content=[[File:US&nbsp;99 (1961).svg|100px]]|caption=The shield for US&nbsp;99|align=left}}\n[[File:Dead-Man's Curve in Lebec, California, 2010.jpg|thumb|right|A section of the 1915 Ridge Route in [[Lebec, California]], abandoned when US&nbsp;99 (later upgraded to I-5) was constructed over the [[Tejon Pass]] in order to make the travel straighter and safer.]]\nAn extensive section of this highway (over {{convert|600|mi|km}}), from approximately [[Stockton, California]], to [[Portland, Oregon]], follows very closely the track of the [[Siskiyou Trail]].<ref name=\"siskiyou\">{{cite web|url=http://www.museumsiskiyoutrail.org |title=Museum of the Siskiyou Trail |publisher=Museumsiskiyoutrail.org |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415171721/http://www.museumsiskiyoutrail.org/ |archivedate=April 15, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> This trail was based on an ancient network of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] footpaths connecting the [[Pacific Northwest]] with California's [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]]. By the 1820s, trappers from the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] were the first non-Native Americans to use the route of today's I-5 to move between today's Washington State and California. During the second half of the 19th century, mule trains, stagecoaches, and the [[Central Pacific Railroad|Central Pacific]] railroad also followed the route of the Siskiyou Trail.<ref name=\"siskiyou\" /> By the early 20th century, pioneering automobile roads were built along the path of the Siskiyou Trail, notably the [[Pacific Highway (United States)|Pacific Highway]]. The Pacific Highway ran from [[British Columbia]] to [[San Diego]], California, and was the immediate predecessor of much of [[U.S. Route 99|US&nbsp;99]]. The route of US&nbsp;99 was in turn used as a basis for much of the route of today's I-5.\n\nA major deviation from the old US&nbsp;99 route is the Westside Freeway portion of I-5 in California's Central Valley. To provide a faster and more direct north\u2013south route through the state, the decision was made to build a new freeway to the west and bypass [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]], and the rest of population centers in the area instead of upgrading the existing highway (which was re-designated as part of [[California State Route 99|SR&nbsp;99]]).<ref name=\"cahighways_5\"/>\nThis re-route through California's Central Valley was the last section of I-5 to be constructed, with the final segment dedicated and opened to traffic near [[Stockton, California]], on October 12, 1979. Representatives from both Canada and Mexico attended the dedication to commemorate the first contiguous freeway connecting the North American countries.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dot.ca.gov/interstate/timeline.htm |author= Staff |publisher= [[California Department of Transportation]] |title= Timeline of Notable Events of the Interstate Highway System in California |accessdate= March 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThis direct route also bypasses [[San Francisco]] and the rest of the [[San Francisco Bay Area]]. Original plans called for a loop Interstate with a directional suffix, I-5W.<ref name=\"cahighways_5\">{{cite web |url= http://www.cahighways.org/001-008.html#005 |work= California Highways |title= Routes 1-8 |accessdate= September 19, 2009}}{{unreliable source?|failed=y|date=March 2014}}</ref> This route now roughly corresponds to [[Interstate 580 (California)|I-580]] from I-5 south of [[Tracy, California|Tracy]] to [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], [[Interstate 80 in California|I-80]] from Oakland to [[Vacaville, California|Vacaville]], and [[Interstate 505|I-505]] from Vacaville to I-5 near [[Dunnigan, California|Dunnigan]]. I-5W and most of the other Interstates around the country with directional suffixes were eventually renumbered or eliminated. Nevertheless, San Francisco is still listed as a [[control city]] on northbound I-5 between SR&nbsp;99 and I-580.\n\nOn May 23, 2013, a portion of a bridge on I-5 [[I-5 Skagit River Bridge collapse|collapsed]] in Washington (near Mount Vernon, between Seattle and the Canada\u2013US border at mile marker 228.3<!-- determined from Google Street View -->), sending two cars into the water and requiring traffic in both directions to bypass the crossing.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.komonews.com/news/local/I-5-Skagit-River-bridge-collapse-caused-by-oversize-load-208813861.html |title= 'Horrified' trucker watches I-5 bridge collapse behind him |first= Manuel |last= Valdes |publisher= [[KOMO-TV]] |location= Seattle |quote= Officials warned it could be weeks before things returned to normal along the heavily travelled corridor. |date= May 24, 2013 |accessdate= May 24, 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130608000441/http://www.komonews.com/news/local/I-5-Skagit-River-bridge-collapse-caused-by-oversize-load-208813861.html |archivedate= June 8, 2013 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Washington State Department of Transportation]] used a temporary structure to restore access across the river while a permanent bridge replacement was built. That process was completed September 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/projects/i5/skagitriverbridgereplacement/ |title = I-5\u2013Skagit River Bridge Replacement |author= Staff |publisher= [[Washington State Department of Transportation]] |accessdate= November 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 18, 2017 [[2017 Washington train derailment|an Amtrak Train derailed by an overpass]] on I-5 near [[Tacoma, Washington]] and blocked several lanes of traffic.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/12/18/amtrak-train-derails-in-washington-state-blocks-interstate-5.html |title= Amtrak train derails in Washington state onto Interstate 5; at least 6 dead |first= Katherine |last= Lam |publisher= [[Fox News]] |date= December 18, 2017 |accessdate= December 18, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the three states started planning a [[charging station|charging network]] for electric trucks along I-5.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carpenter |first1=Susan |title=Truckers Can Expect an Electrified West Coast Corridor |url=https://www.trucks.com/2019/05/24/truckers-electrified-west-coast-corridor/ |website=Trucks.com |date=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Junction list==\n[[File:I-90 and I-5 cloverleaf seattle washington.jpg|thumb|upright|Looking South at I-5 and [[Interstate 90|I-90]] meeting in [[Seattle]].]]\n[[File:SanYsidroBorderCrossingByPhilKonstantin.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of the [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]] border crossing on the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican border]], marking where I-5 continues south at [[Mexico Federal Highway 1]].]]\n[[File:Peace Arch, U.S.-Canada border.jpg|thumb|The [[Peace Arch]] monument on the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian border]], marking where I-5 continues north as [[British Columbia Highway 99]].]]\n;California\n: {{jct|state=BCN|FH|1}} at the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican border]] in [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|805}} in San Ysidro\n: {{jct|state=CA|SR|905}} on the [[Nestor, San Diego|Nestor]]\u2013San Ysidro\u2013[[Otay Mesa West, San Diego|Otay Mesa West]] neighborhood line (future I-905)\n: {{jct|state=CA|SR|15}} on the [[Barrio Logan, San Diego|Barrio Logan]]\u2013[[Southcrest, San Diego|Southcrest]]\u2013[[Logan Heights, San Diego|Logan Heights]] neighborhood line (future I-15)\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|8}} in [[San Diego]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=California}} in [[Irvine, California|Irvine]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|605}} on the [[Downey, California|Downey]]\u2013[[Santa Fe Springs, California|Santa Fe Springs]] city line\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|710}} in [[Commerce, California|Commerce]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|101}} in [[Los Angeles]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|10}} in [[Boyle Heights, Los Angeles|Boyle Heights]]. The highways travel concurrently through Boyle Heights.\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=California}} on the [[Mission Hills, Los Angeles|Mission Hills]]\u2013[[Granada Hills, Los Angeles|Granada Hills]] neighborhood line\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|210|dab1=California}} in [[Sylmar, Los Angeles|Sylmar]]\n: {{jct|state=CA|SR|99}} in [[Wheeler Ridge, California|Wheeler Ridge]] (Former US&nbsp;99, future I-7 or I-9)\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|580|dab1=California}} southwest of [[Vernalis, California|Vernalis]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|205|dab1=California}} south-southwest of [[Lathrop, California|Lathrop]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|305|dab1=California|US|50}} in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|80}} in Sacramento\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|505}} south-southeast of [[Dunnigan, California|Dunnigan]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|97}} in [[Weed, California|Weed]]\n;Oregon\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|199}} east of [[Grants Pass, Oregon|Grants Pass]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|105|dab1=Oregon}} on the [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]]\u2013[[Springfield, Oregon|Springfield]] city line\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|20}} in [[Albany, Oregon|Albany]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|205|dab1=Oregon\u2013Washington}} in [[Tualatin, Oregon|Tualatin]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|26}} in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=Oregon}} in Portland\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|84|dab1=Oregon\u2013Utah|US|30}} in Portland. I-5/US&nbsp;30 travels concurrently through Portland.\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=Oregon|US|30}} in Portland\n;Washington\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|205|dab1=Oregon\u2013Washington}} on the [[Salmon Creek, Washington|Salmon Creek]]\u2013[[Mount Vista, Washington|Mount Vista]] CDP line\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|12}} south-southeast of [[Napavine, Washington|Napavine]]. The highways travel concurrently to [[Grand Mound, Washington|Grand Mound]].\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|101}} in [[Tumwater, Washington|Tumwater]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|705}} in [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=Washington}} in [[Tukwila, Washington|Tukwila]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|90}} in [[Seattle]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=Washington}} on the [[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]]\u2013[[Martha Lake, Washington|Martha Lake]]\u2013[[Alderwood Manor, Washington|Alderwood Manor]] line\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|2}} in [[Everett, Washington|Everett]]\n: {{jct|province=BC|BC|99}} at the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canada\u2013US border]] in [[Blaine, Washington|Blaine]]\n\n==Auxiliary routes==\n* [[San Diego]], California\u2014[[Interstate 805|I-805]]\n* [[Los Angeles]], California\u2014[[Interstate 105 (California)|I-105]]\n* Los Angeles and [[Orange County, California]]\u2014[[Interstate 605|I-605]]\n* Los Angeles and Orange County, California\u2014[[Interstate 405 (California)|I-405]]\n* [[Tracy, California]]\u2014[[Interstate 205 (California)|I-205]]\n* [[Sacramento, California]]\u2014[[Interstate 305 (California)|I-305]] (unsigned)\n* [[Zamora, California]]\u2014[[Interstate 505 (California)|I-505]]\n* [[Eugene, Oregon]]\u2014[[Oregon Route 126|I-105]]\n* [[Portland, Oregon]]\u2014[[Interstate 405 (Oregon)|I-405]]\n* Portland, Oregon, and [[Vancouver, Washington]]\u2014[[Interstate 205 (Oregon\u2013Washington)|I-205]]\n* [[Tacoma, Washington]]\u2014[[Interstate 705|I-705]]\n* [[Seattle]], Washington\u2014[[Interstate 405 (Washington)|I-405]]\n\nI-5 will have a complete set of auxiliary routes (i.e. 105, 205, 305, 405, 505, 605, 705, 805, 905), with the completion of I-905 in [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]]. Currently, [[Interstate 80|I-80]] and [[Interstate 90|I-90]] are the only two Interstates to have complete sets of auxiliary routes.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Interstate 5}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Interstate 5}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n*{{osmrelation-inline}}\n*[http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-005.html Interstate 5] at the Interstate Guide\n\n{{interstates}}\n{{I-5 aux}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I05}}\n[[Category:Interstate Highway System|05]]\n[[Category:Interstate 5| ]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 99|Interstate 05]]\n[[Category:Roads with a reversible lane|05]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|I-5||I5 (disambiguation)}}\n{{For|the Wedding Present song|Interstate 5 (song)}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Short description|Interstate along the West Coast of the US}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=USA\n|type=I\n|route=5\n|length_mi=1381.29\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"fhwa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/reports/routefinder/table1.cfm|work=Route Log and Finder List |title= Table 1: Main Routes of the Dwight D. Eisenhower National System Of Interstate and Defense Highways as of December 31, 2013 |date= December 31, 2013 |author= Staff |publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]]|accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref>\n|history=Designated in 1956<br/>Completed in 1979\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=BCN|FH|1}} at the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican border]] at [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro, CA]]\n|junction=<!-- Major junctions ONLY; Only 5-7 most major intersections and cities belong here; please read [[WP:USRD/STDS]] for more info; please do not add any more! -->{{plainlist|1=\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|15}} to [[Interstate 15|I-15]] in [[San Diego|San Diego, CA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|8}} in San Diego, CA\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|10|US|101}} in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, CA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|US|50}} in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento, CA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|80}} in Sacramento, CA\n*{{jct|country=USA|US|20}} in [[Albany, Oregon|Albany, OR]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|84|dab1= Oregon\u2013Utah|US|30}} in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland, OR]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|US|101}} in [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia, WA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|90}} in [[Seattle|Seattle, WA]]\n*{{jct|country=USA|US|2}} in [[Everett, Washington|Everett, WA]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{jct|province=BC|BC|99}} at the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canada\u2013US border]] at [[Blaine, Washington|Blaine, WA]]\n|states=[[California]], [[Oregon]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n}}\n'''Interstate 5''' ('''I-5''') is the main north\u2013south [[Interstate Highway System|Interstate Highway]] on the [[West Coast of the United States]], running largely parallel to the [[Pacific coast]] of the contiguous U.S. from [[Mexico]] to [[Canada]]. It travels through the states of [[California]], [[Oregon]], and [[Washington (state)|Washington]], serving several large cities on the U.S. West Coast, including [[San Diego]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], and [[Seattle]]. It is the only continuous Interstate highway to touch both the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican]] and the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian]] borders. Upon crossing the Mexican border at its southern terminus, I-5 continues to [[Tijuana]], Baja California, as [[Mexico Federal Highway 1]] (Fed.&nbsp;1). Upon crossing the Canadian border at its northern terminus, it continues to [[Vancouver]] as [[British Columbia Highway 99]] (BC&nbsp;99).\n\nI-5 was originally created in 1956 as part of the Interstate Highway System, but it was predated by several auto trails and highways built in the early 20th century. The Pacific Highway auto trail was built in the 1910s and 1920s by the states of California, Oregon, and Washington, and was later incorporated into [[U.S. Route 99]] (US&nbsp;99) in 1926. I-5 largely follows the route of US&nbsp;99, with the exception of a portion in the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] of California. The freeway was built in segments between 1956 and 1978, including expressway sections of US&nbsp;99 that were built earlier to bypass various towns along the route.\n\n==Route description==\n{{lengths table|length_ref=<ref name=\"fhwa\" />}}\n|-\n|[[Interstate 5 in California|CA]]\n|{{convert|796.53|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[Interstate 5 in Oregon|OR]]\n|{{convert|308.14|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|[[Interstate 5 in Washington|WA]]\n|{{convert|276.62|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|-\n|Total\n|{{convert|1381.29|mi|km|disp=table}}\n|}\n\n===California===\n[[File:Interstate5newhallpass.JPG|thumb|right|I-5 in the [[Newhall Pass Interchange]] where it intersects with [[Interstate 210 and State Route 210 (California)|I-210]] and [[California State Route 14|State Route 14]] near [[Santa Clarita, California|Santa Clarita]] ]]\n{{main|Interstate 5 in California}}\nThe southernmost point of I-5 is at the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican border]] at the [[San Ysidro Port of Entry]], one of the busiest border crossings in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-005.html |title=Busiest border crossing |publisher=Interstate-guide.com |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2011}}{{unreliable source?|failed=y|date=March 2014}}</ref> Beginning at the border in [[San Ysidro, San Deigeo|San Ysidro]] which is part of the city of [[San Diego]], as the [[John J. Montgomery Freeway]], I-5 goes through the suburbs of [[Chula Vista, California|Chula Vista]] and [[National City, California|National City]] before reaching downtown San Diego. It then parallels the Pacific coastline, going through the northern suburbs of San Diego, bisecting the [[University of California, San Diego]] campus, and passing the I-805 merge (where it becomes the widest Interstate in the United States for a short stretch), before passing through several [[North County (San Diego area)|North County]] coastal suburbs and then through {{convert|18|mi|km}} of [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] Base [[Camp Pendleton, California|Camp Pendleton]] in northern [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]]. Here I-5 is also known as the San Diego Freeway.\n\nAt [[Dana Point, California|Dana Point]], I-5 turns inland and heads due north through [[Mission Viejo, California|Mission Viejo]] to the [[El Toro Y]] interchange in southeastern [[Irvine, California|Irvine]]. I-5 becomes the [[Santa Ana Freeway]] as it runs southeast to northwest, passing through major cities and suburbs in [[Orange County, California|Orange]] and [[Los Angeles County, California|Southern Los Angeles]] counties. Southern Californians often refer to it as \"the 5\" or as the Santa Ana Freeway in the Los Angeles area. From this point, the San Diego Freeway continues northward as I-405.\n\nWhen the freeway reaches the [[East Los Angeles Interchange]] {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} east of downtown [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], I-5 becomes the [[Golden State Freeway]]. The route continues through the [[San Fernando Valley]] and then crosses the [[Newhall Pass]] through the [[Santa Susana Mountains]] into the [[Santa Clarita Valley]]. The interchange with [[California State Route 14|State Route 14]] (SR&nbsp;14) is unusual in that truck traffic is separated into its own lanes for both the mainline of the freeway and the transition ramps to and from SR&nbsp;14. For about a {{convert|5|mi|km|adj=on|spell=in}} stretch between the Santa Clarita Valley and [[Pyramid Lake (Los Angeles County, California)|Pyramid Lake]], the northbound and southbound lanes separate and cross sides, with the southbound lanes running to the east of the northbound ones. At that point, the Golden State Freeway rises sharply to the north through [[Ridge Route#Features|the Grapevine]] to eventually reach the second-highest point of its entire length, the [[Tejon Pass]] (elevation {{convert|4144|ft|m|abbr=on|disp=or}}). Through the [[Tehachapi Mountains]]. [[Path 26]] [[electric power transmission|power lines]] generally follow the freeway along this stretch. The freeway then descends sharply for {{convert|12|mi|km}} at Tejon Pass to around {{convert|1500|ft|m}} at Grapevine near the southernmost point of the [[San Joaquin Valley]], approximately {{convert|30|mi|km}} south of [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]] and {{convert|5|mi|km|abbr=on}} south from where [[California State Route 99|SR&nbsp;99]] splits away from it in [[Wheeler Ridge, California|Wheeler Ridge]].\n\n[[File:I-5 near Shasta.jpg|thumb|left|I-5 south approaching Weed and Mount Shasta]]\n\nFrom SR&nbsp;99 to south of [[Tracy, California|Tracy]], I-5 skirts along the far more remote western edge of the great [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]], and thus here is removed from population centers such as [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]] and [[Fresno, California|Fresno]]; other state highways provide these connections. This part of I-5 is known as the West Side Freeway, and is a major connector between the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] and Southern California. [[Interstate 580 (California)|I-580]] splits from I-5 at a point south of Tracy as the West Side Freeway Scenic Byway, the last stretch of the West Side Freeway\u2014providing a loop-route connection to the San Francisco Bay Area. East of Tracy, I-5 intersects with I-205, another freeway that links I-5 to the Bay Area and passes through Tracy. After passing Tracy, I-5 heads north through [[Stockton, California|Stockton]] and [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] before turning west to [[Woodland, California|Woodland]]. At Woodland, the Interstate heads northwest again towards [[Dunnigan, California|Dunnigan]], where it converges with [[Interstate 505|I-505]].\n\nFrom Dunnigan, I-5 skirts north along the western edge of the [[Sacramento Valley]] to [[Red Bluff, California|Red Bluff]]. I-5 then enters the [[Shasta Cascade]] region, passing through [[Redding, California|Redding]] and [[Shasta Lake]] before climbing up to near the foot of [[Mount Shasta]]. The interstate then travels to [[Weed, California|Weed]] and [[Yreka, California|Yreka]] before reaching the Oregon border.\n\n===Oregon===\n{{main|Interstate 5 in Oregon}}\n[[File:I5inPortlandNight.jpg|right|thumb|I-5 running adjacent to the [[Willamette River]] and passes by the [[Moda Center]], and [[Oregon Convention Center]] in Downtown Portland]]\nAbout {{convert|3|mi|km|spell=in}} north of the California border, the highway crosses {{convert|4310|ft|m}} [[Siskiyou Summit]], the highest point on I-5, and then drops down into the [[Rogue Valley]] through Oregon's southern mountains and towns such as [[Ashland, Oregon|Ashland]], [[Medford, Oregon|Medford]] and [[Grants Pass, Oregon|Grants Pass]]. Turning north across three passes to the Umpqua Valley and through [[Roseburg, Oregon|Roseburg]], the mountains tend to turn into hills, and as it reaches Cottage Grove, the road enters the [[Willamette Valley|Willamette River Valley]]. At [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]] the highway intersects [[Oregon Route 126|I-105]], a short spur route into Downtown [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]]. Some city highways intersect on I-5 in the Eugene Metro. The Interstate then heads almost due north, skirting [[Albany, Oregon|Albany]] and [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]], passing through [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]], and crossing through [[Woodburn, Oregon|Woodburn]]. There were plans to build a spur, called [[Interstate 305 (Oregon)|I-305]], into Salem. I-5 covers {{convert|308|mi|km}} in [[Oregon]].\n\nJust north of Salem, between mile markers 259 and 260 just short of mile marker 260, signs in the median and on both shoulders mark the place where the [[45th parallel north|45th parallel]] crosses I-5. It reads \"45th Parallel half way between the Equator and the North Pole\".\n\nThe highway then tracks a little to the northeast, and [[Interstate 205 (Oregon\u2013Washington)|I-205]] splits off south of the [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] metro area. From here I-5 passes through Tualatin and Tigard along former [[U.S. Route 99W (Oregon)|U.S. Route 99W]] (US&nbsp;99W) before hitting the southern terminus of [[Interstate 405 (Oregon)|I-405]] and the [[Marquam Bridge]]. Also planned was a spur in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] off I-405, called [[Interstate 505 (Oregon)|I-505]], but it was never built and has been removed from city plans. A stub of I-505 exists as a long exit ramp to [[U.S. Route 30|US&nbsp;30]].\n\nAfter crossing the Willamette River on the [[Marquam Bridge]], I-5 has junctions at the western end of [[Interstate 84 in Oregon|I-84]] and the northern end of I-405. It then continues through the northern parts of the city of Portland, and crosses into Washington via the [[Interstate Bridge]].\n\n===Washington===\n{{main|Interstate 5 in Washington}}\n[[File:SeattleI5Skyline.jpg|thumb|right|I-5 passing through downtown Seattle]]\nThe highway continues over the [[Columbia River]] and drops down into the city of [[Vancouver, Washington|Vancouver]]. About {{convert|7|mi|km|spell=in}} into the state, it reaches the northern terminus of [[Interstate 205 (Oregon\u2013Washington)|I-205]], which is on the eastern edge of the Portland\u2013Vancouver metropolitan area. It then tracks north by northwest through [[Woodland, Washington|Woodland]] to [[Kelso, Washington|Kelso]] and [[Longview, Washington|Longview]], at which point it ceases to parallel a large bend of the Columbia River. Continuing north between the [[Willapa Hills]] and the Cascade foothills, the freeway eventually reaches [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia]], where it bends sharply east. The highway passes through the northern end of [[Joint Base Lewis-McChord]] (formerly [[Fort Lewis]] and [[McChord Field|McChord Air Force Base]]) and [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]], where it bends sharply north again to reach [[Seattle]]. The [[Ship Canal Bridge]] carries it over [[Portage Bay]] in Seattle. The freeway continues north out of the Seattle\u2013Tacoma\u2013[[Everett, Washington|Everett]] metro area, crosses the floodplains of three rivers, through the Skagit Valley and the Mount Vernon\u2013Burlington Metropolitan Area to the northern city of [[Bellingham, Washington|Bellingham]], to arrive at the [[Peace Arch]] Canada\u2013US border crossing between [[Blaine, Washington]], and [[Surrey, British Columbia]]. [[British Columbia Highway 99|Highway 99]] continues northwest from the border into [[Vancouver|Vancouver, BC]]. I-5 covers {{convert|277|mi|km}} in Washington.\n\n==History==\n{{imageframe|width=100|content=[[File:US&nbsp;99 (1961).svg|100px]]|caption=The shield for US&nbsp;99|align=left}}\n[[File:Dead-Man's Curve in Lebec, California, 2010.jpg|thumb|right|A section of the 1915 Ridge Route in [[Lebec, California]], abandoned when US&nbsp;99 (later upgraded to I-5) was constructed over the [[Tejon Pass]] in order to make the travel straighter and safer.]]\nAn extensive section of this highway (over {{convert|600|mi|km}}), from approximately [[Stockton, California]], to [[Portland, Oregon]], follows very closely the track of the [[Siskiyou Trail]].<ref name=\"siskiyou\">{{cite web|url=http://www.museumsiskiyoutrail.org |title=Museum of the Siskiyou Trail |publisher=Museumsiskiyoutrail.org |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415171721/http://www.museumsiskiyoutrail.org/ |archivedate=April 15, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> This trail was based on an ancient network of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] footpaths connecting the [[Pacific Northwest]] with California's [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]]. By the 1820s, trappers from the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] were the first non-Native Americans to use the route of today's I-5 to move between today's Washington State and California. During the second half of the 19th century, mule trains, stagecoaches, and the [[Central Pacific Railroad|Central Pacific]] railroad also followed the route of the Siskiyou Trail.<ref name=\"siskiyou\" /> By the early 20th century, pioneering automobile roads were built along the path of the Siskiyou Trail, notably the [[Pacific Highway (United States)|Pacific Highway]]. The Pacific Highway ran from [[British Columbia]] to [[San Diego]], California, and was the immediate predecessor of much of [[U.S. Route 99|US&nbsp;99]]. The route of US&nbsp;99 was in turn used as a basis for much of the route of today's I-5.\n\nA major deviation from the old US&nbsp;99 route is the Westside Freeway portion of I-5 in California's Central Valley. To provide a faster and more direct north\u2013south route through the state, the decision was made to build a new freeway to the west and bypass [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]], and the rest of population centers in the area instead of upgrading the existing highway (which was re-designated as part of [[California State Route 99|SR&nbsp;99]]).<ref name=\"cahighways_5\"/>\nThis re-route through California's Central Valley was the last section of I-5 to be constructed, with the final segment dedicated and opened to traffic near [[Stockton, California]], on October 12, 1979. Representatives from both Canada and Mexico attended the dedication to commemorate the first contiguous freeway connecting the North American countries.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dot.ca.gov/interstate/timeline.htm |author= Staff |publisher= [[California Department of Transportation]] |title= Timeline of Notable Events of the Interstate Highway System in California |accessdate= March 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThis direct route also bypasses [[San Francisco]] and the rest of the [[San Francisco Bay Area]]. Original plans called for a loop Interstate with a directional suffix, I-5W.<ref name=\"cahighways_5\">{{cite web |url= http://www.cahighways.org/001-008.html#005 |work= California Highways |title= Routes 1-8 |accessdate= September 19, 2009}}{{unreliable source?|failed=y|date=March 2014}}</ref> This route now roughly corresponds to [[Interstate 580 (California)|I-580]] from I-5 south of [[Tracy, California|Tracy]] to [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], [[Interstate 80 in California|I-80]] from Oakland to [[Vacaville, California|Vacaville]], and [[Interstate 505|I-505]] from Vacaville to I-5 near [[Dunnigan, California|Dunnigan]]. I-5W and most of the other Interstates around the country with directional suffixes were eventually renumbered or eliminated. Nevertheless, San Francisco is still listed as a [[control city]] on northbound I-5 between SR&nbsp;99 and I-580.\n\nOn May 23, 2013, a portion of a bridge on I-5 [[I-5 Skagit River Bridge collapse|collapsed]] in Washington (near Mount Vernon, between Seattle and the Canada\u2013US border at mile marker 228.3<!-- determined from Google Street View -->), sending two cars into the water and requiring traffic in both directions to bypass the crossing.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.komonews.com/news/local/I-5-Skagit-River-bridge-collapse-caused-by-oversize-load-208813861.html |title= 'Horrified' trucker watches I-5 bridge collapse behind him |first= Manuel |last= Valdes |publisher= [[KOMO-TV]] |location= Seattle |quote= Officials warned it could be weeks before things returned to normal along the heavily travelled corridor. |date= May 24, 2013 |accessdate= May 24, 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130608000441/http://www.komonews.com/news/local/I-5-Skagit-River-bridge-collapse-caused-by-oversize-load-208813861.html |archivedate= June 8, 2013 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Washington State Department of Transportation]] used a temporary structure to restore access across the river while a permanent bridge replacement was built. That process was completed September 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wsdot.wa.gov/projects/i5/skagitriverbridgereplacement/ |title = I-5\u2013Skagit River Bridge Replacement |author= Staff |publisher= [[Washington State Department of Transportation]] |accessdate= November 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 18, 2017 [[2017 Washington train derailment|an Amtrak Train derailed by an overpass]] on I-5 near [[Tacoma, Washington]] and blocked several lanes of traffic.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/12/18/amtrak-train-derails-in-washington-state-blocks-interstate-5.html |title= Amtrak train derails in Washington state onto Interstate 5; at least 6 dead |first= Katherine |last= Lam |publisher= [[Fox News]] |date= December 18, 2017 |accessdate= December 18, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the three states started planning a [[charging station|charging network]] for electric trucks along I-5.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carpenter |first1=Susan |title=Truckers Can Expect an Electrified West Coast Corridor |url=https://www.trucks.com/2019/05/24/truckers-electrified-west-coast-corridor/ |website=Trucks.com |date=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Junction list==\n[[File:I-90 and I-5 cloverleaf seattle washington.jpg|thumb|upright|Looking South at I-5 and [[Interstate 90|I-90]] meeting in [[Seattle]].]]\n[[File:SanYsidroBorderCrossingByPhilKonstantin.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of the [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]] border crossing on the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican border]], marking where I-5 continues south at [[Mexico Federal Highway 1]].]]\n[[File:Peace Arch, U.S.-Canada border.jpg|thumb|The [[Peace Arch]] monument on the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian border]], marking where I-5 continues north as [[British Columbia Highway 99]].]]\n;California\n: {{jct|state=BCN|FH|1}} at the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexican border]] in [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|805}} in San Ysidro\n: {{jct|state=CA|SR|905}} on the [[Nestor, San Diego|Nestor]]\u2013San Ysidro\u2013[[Otay Mesa West, San Diego|Otay Mesa West]] neighborhood line (future I-905)\n: {{jct|state=CA|SR|15}} on the [[Barrio Logan, San Diego|Barrio Logan]]\u2013[[Southcrest, San Diego|Southcrest]]\u2013[[Logan Heights, San Diego|Logan Heights]] neighborhood line (future I-15)\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|8}} in [[San Diego]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=California}} in [[Irvine, California|Irvine]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|605}} on the [[Downey, California|Downey]]\u2013[[Santa Fe Springs, California|Santa Fe Springs]] city line\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|710}} in [[Commerce, California|Commerce]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|101}} in [[Los Angeles]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|10}} in [[Boyle Heights, Los Angeles|Boyle Heights]]. The highways travel concurrently through Boyle Heights.\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=California}} on the [[Mission Hills, Los Angeles|Mission Hills]]\u2013[[Granada Hills, Los Angeles|Granada Hills]] neighborhood line\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|210|dab1=California}} in [[Sylmar, Los Angeles|Sylmar]]\n: {{jct|state=CA|SR|99}} in [[Wheeler Ridge, California|Wheeler Ridge]] (Former US&nbsp;99, future I-7 or I-9)\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|580|dab1=California}} southwest of [[Vernalis, California|Vernalis]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|205|dab1=California}} south-southwest of [[Lathrop, California|Lathrop]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|305|dab1=California|US|50}} in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|80}} in Sacramento\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|505}} south-southeast of [[Dunnigan, California|Dunnigan]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|97}} in [[Weed, California|Weed]]\n;Oregon\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|199}} east of [[Grants Pass, Oregon|Grants Pass]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|105|dab1=Oregon}} on the [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]]\u2013[[Springfield, Oregon|Springfield]] city line\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|20}} in [[Albany, Oregon|Albany]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|205|dab1=Oregon\u2013Washington}} in [[Tualatin, Oregon|Tualatin]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|26}} in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=Oregon}} in Portland\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|84|dab1=Oregon\u2013Utah|US|30}} in Portland. I-5/US&nbsp;30 travels concurrently through Portland.\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=Oregon|US|30}} in Portland\n;Washington\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|205|dab1=Oregon\u2013Washington}} on the [[Salmon Creek, Washington|Salmon Creek]]\u2013[[Mount Vista, Washington|Mount Vista]] CDP line\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|12}} south-southeast of [[Napavine, Washington|Napavine]]. The highways travel concurrently to [[Grand Mound, Washington|Grand Mound]].\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|101}} in [[Tumwater, Washington|Tumwater]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|705}} in [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=Washington}} in [[Tukwila, Washington|Tukwila]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|90}} in [[Seattle]]\n: {{jct|country=USA|I|405|dab1=Washington}} on the [[Lynnwood, Washington|Lynnwood]]\u2013[[Martha Lake, Washington|Martha Lake]]\u2013[[Alderwood Manor, Washington|Alderwood Manor]] line\n: {{jct|country=USA|US|2}} in [[Everett, Washington|Everett]]\n: {{jct|province=BC|BC|99}} at the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canada\u2013US border]] in [[Blaine, Washington|Blaine]]\n\n==Auxiliary routes==\n* [[San Diego]], California\u2014[[Interstate 805|I-805]]\n* [[Los Angeles]], California\u2014[[Interstate 105 (California)|I-105]]\n* Los Angeles and [[Orange County, California]]\u2014[[Interstate 605|I-605]]\n* Los Angeles and Orange County, California\u2014[[Interstate 405 (California)|I-405]]\n* [[Tracy, California]]\u2014[[Interstate 205 (California)|I-205]]\n* [[Sacramento, California]]\u2014[[Interstate 305 (California)|I-305]] (unsigned)\n* [[Zamora, California]]\u2014[[Interstate 505 (California)|I-505]]\n* [[Eugene, Oregon]]\u2014[[Oregon Route 126|I-105]]\n* [[Portland, Oregon]]\u2014[[Interstate 405 (Oregon)|I-405]]\n* Portland, Oregon, and [[Vancouver, Washington]]\u2014[[Interstate 205 (Oregon\u2013Washington)|I-205]]\n* [[Tacoma, Washington]]\u2014[[Interstate 705|I-705]]\n* [[Seattle]], Washington\u2014[[Interstate 405 (Washington)|I-405]]\n\nI-5 will have a complete set of auxiliary routes (i.e. 105, 205, 305, 405, 505, 605, 705, 805, 905), with the completion of I-905 in [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]]. Currently, [[Interstate 80|I-80]] and [[Interstate 90|I-90]] are the only two Interstates to have complete sets of auxiliary routes.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n