{"title_page": "Alasdair McDonnell", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Alasdair McDonnell\n|image        = Alasdair McDonnell MP.JPG\n|office       = Leader of the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]]\n|term_start   = 5 November 2011\n|term_end     = 14 November 2015\n|predecessor  = [[Margaret Ritchie (politician)|Margaret Ritchie]]\n|successor    = [[Colum Eastwood]]\n|office1      = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Belfast South (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast South]]\n|term_start1  = 5 May 2005\n|term_end1    = 3 May 2017 \n|predecessor1 = [[Martin Smyth]]\n|successor1   = [[Emma Little-Pengelly]]\n|office2      = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]]<br />for [[Belfast South (Assembly constituency)|Belfast South]]\n|term_start2  = 25 June 1998\n|term_end2    = 21 June 2015\n|predecessor2 = Constituency established\n|successor2   = [[Claire Hanna (politician)|Claire Hanna]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1949|9|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Cushendall]], [[County Antrim]], [[Northern Ireland]]\n|death_date   = \n|party        = [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]]\n|spouse       = Olivia Nugent\n|children     = 4\n|alma_mater   = [[University College Dublin]]\n|website      = {{url|alasdairmcdonnell.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Alasdair McDonnell''' (born 1 September 1949) is an Irish politician who is a member of the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] (SDLP), and was its leader from 2011 to 2015. He was the Member of Parliament for [[Belfast South (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast South]] from 2005 to 2017<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url= http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/video-news/video-sdlps-dr-alasdair-mcdonnell-loses-south-belfast-seat-35808197.html|title= Video: SDLP's Dr Alasdair McDonnell loses South Belfast seat|work= [[Belfast Telegraph]]|author= Grattan, Gary|date= 9 June 2017|access-date= 9 June 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180117190543/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/video-news/video-sdlps-dr-alasdair-mcdonnell-loses-south-belfast-seat-35808197.html|archive-date= 17 January 2018|url-status= live}}</ref> and also a [[Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] of Northern Ireland for [[Belfast South (Assembly constituency)|Belfast South]] from 1998 to 2015.<ref name=RTE1>[http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1105/sdlp.html \"Alasdair McDonnell elected SDLP leader\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106124346/http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1105/sdlp.html |date=6 November 2011 }}, rte.ie, 5 November 2011.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n{{BLP sources section|date=May 2016}}\nMcDonnell's first involvement with [[Politics of Northern Ireland|politics]] came when he joined the [[National Democrats (Northern Ireland)|National Democrats]] and stood as the [[Parliamentary candidate|party candidate]] in the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 election]] in [[North Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|North Antrim]] and lost to [[Ian Paisley]].<ref>[http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/dna.htm North Antrim 1950\u20131970] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504050726/http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/dna.htm |date=4 May 2009 }}, ARK.ac.uk; accessed 15 May 2016.</ref>\n\nMcDonnell first won election to [[Belfast City Council]] in [[1977 Northern Ireland local elections|1977]], representing Belfast \"Area A\" which included the [[Short Strand]] and [[Ormeau Road|Upper Ormeau]] areas. He lost his council seat in a surprise result in [[1981 Northern Ireland local elections|1981]] but returned in [[1985 Northern Ireland local elections|1985]] and served as the first Catholic [[Mayor of Belfast|Deputy Mayor of Belfast]] in 1995\u201396.\n\nHe first stood for the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Westminster]] [[Belfast South (UK Parliament constituency)|constituency of South Belfast]] in the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 general election]] and subsequently contested the constituency at each subsequent general election, though not in the 1986 by-election (caused by the resignation of [[Unionists (Ireland)|Unionist]] MPs in protest at the [[Anglo Irish Agreement]]). He was also elected from the constituency to the [[Northern Ireland Peace Forum]] in 1996 and the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] in [[1998 Northern Ireland Assembly election|1998]] and [[2003 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2003]].\n\nIn 2004 he became his party's deputy leader. In the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] McDonnell generated one of the most sensational results in Northern Ireland when he won South Belfast, primarily due to a split in the [[Unionists (Ireland)|unionist]] vote. He received 10,339 votes while the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] (DUP) candidate Jimmy Spratt received 9,104 votes and [[Ulster Unionist Party]] candidate [[Michael McGimpsey]] received 7,263 votes. He was then re-elected by an increased majority in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]]. On 5 November 2011, he was elected leader of the SDLP at its conference in Belfast, succeeding [[Margaret Ritchie (politician)|Margaret Ritchie]].<ref name=\"RTE1\"/>\n\nIn a 2012 interview with ''[[The News Letter]]'', McDonnell criticised [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. He said the party were run along \"Soviet style\" lines where there was a military structure and where former terrorists were being placed into positions of power. He also claimed many people voting for Sinn F\u00e9in were doing so as an act of defiance.<ref name=\"McBride\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/ni-news/co-tyrone/sdlp-scorn-for-soviet-style-sf-1-4138356|title=SDLP scorn for Soviet style SF|work=[[The News Letter]]|date=8 August 2012|accessdate=1 June 2015|author=McBride, Sam}}</ref>\n\nAs SDLP chief, McDonnell described the terms of the [[Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies]], a seemingly blocked plan to reduce the number of MPs in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] by 50 (including two from Northern Ireland) to 600, as \"a bureaucratic numbers game initiated by [[Conservative Party (UK)|the Tories]] for purely party political advantage\".<ref name=\"Clarke\">{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/politics/sdlp-chief-alasdair-mcdonnell-relishes-coalition-row-that-could-save-his-seat-28778816.html|title=SDLP chief Alasdair McDonnell relishes coalition row that could save his seat|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|date=8 August 2012|accessdate=1 June 2015|author=Clarke, Liam|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611003309/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/politics/sdlp-chief-alasdair-mcdonnell-relishes-coalition-row-that-could-save-his-seat-28778816.html|archive-date=11 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, the SDLP abstained during the vote on the Civil Service (Special Advisers) Bill<ref name=\"NIAssembly\">{{cite news|url=http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/assembly-business/legislation/current-non-executive-bill-proposals/civil-service-special-advisers-bill |title=NI Assembly Civil Service (Special Advisers) Bill |date=8 July 2013 |accessdate=8 April 2015 |work=NI Assembly |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413121628/http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/assembly-business/legislation/current-non-executive-bill-proposals/civil-service-special-advisers-bill/ |archivedate=13 April 2015 }}</ref> in [[Stormont, Belfast|Stormont]], ensuring its passing. This led to claims from [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] that the SDLP was endorsing a 'hierarchy of victims' agenda and abandoning the principles of the [[Good Friday Agreement]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-22759895|title=Special adviser bill passed after marathon Stormont debate|date=4 June 2013|accessdate=5 June 2013|work=[[BBC News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604014930/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-22759895|archive-date=4 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDespite the reported claims<ref name=\"BBC\"/> from Sinn F\u00e9in that it was inevitable that someone would mount a legal challenge to \"what republicans view as a discriminatory law\" no such challenge has since emerged. In the [[2015 United Kingdom general election]] he stood again in Belfast South and was returned on 24.5% of the vote, the lowest ever vote share recorded by a successful MP in any part of the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/ni-politics/mcdonnell-won-s-belfast-with-lowest-ever-vote-share-by-a-uk-mp-1-6735240|title=McDonnell won S. Belfast with lowest ever vote share by a UK MP|first=Ben|last=Lowry|work=[[The News Letter]]|date=9 May 2015|accessdate=24 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131003823/http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/ni-politics/mcdonnell-won-s-belfast-with-lowest-ever-vote-share-by-a-uk-mp-1-6735240|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 November 2015, McDonnell lost the leadership contest held at the SDLP's annual conference. His successor as leader of the party, [[Colum Eastwood]], won with 172 votes to the 133 that McDonnell received.<ref>{{cite web|title=SDLP leadership: Colum Eastwood wins contest against Alasdair McDonnell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-34822651|website=BBC News|accessdate=14 November 2015|date=14 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114234835/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-34822651|archive-date=14 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2017, McDonnell lost his South Belfast seat to [[Emma Little-Pengelly]] (DUP) in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.alasdairmcdonnell.com/ Alasdair McDonnell official website]\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=dr-alasdair-mcdonnell/1596 |publicwhip=Alasdair_McDonnell |theywork=alasdair_mcdonnell}}\n*[http://www.stratagem-ni.com/politician_specific.aspx?dataid=357958 Profile]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, stratagem-ni.com\n*[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-9665,00.html Profile], Guardian.co.uk\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050615/debtext/50615-17.htm Maiden Speech: House of Commons \u2013 15 June 2005]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ian Adamson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord Mayor of Belfast|Deputy Lord Mayor of Belfast]]|years=1995\u20131996}}\n{{s-aft|after=Margaret Crooks}}\n\n{{s-par|ni/for}}\n{{s-new|forum}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Northern Ireland Forum]]<br />[[South Belfast (Assembly constituency)|South Belfast]]|years=1996\u20131998}}\n{{s-non|reason=Forum dissolved}}\n\n{{s-par|ni/ass}}\n{{s-new|Assembly }}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]]<br />for [[Belfast South (Assembly constituency)|Belfast South]]|years=1998\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Claire Hanna (politician)|Claire Hanna]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Martin Smyth]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Belfast South (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast South]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emma Little-Pengelly]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Margaret Ritchie (politician)|Margaret Ritchie]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Colum Eastwood]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Social Democratic and Labour Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McDonnell, Alasdair}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of Belfast City Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Belfast constituencies (since 1922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Northern Ireland Forum]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Party (Northern Ireland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 1998\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2003\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2007\u20132011]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2011\u20132016]]\n[[Category:People from Cushendall]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic and Labour Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic and Labour Party MPs (UK)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Alasdair McDonnell\n|image        = Alasdair McDonnell MP.JPG\n|office       = Leader of the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]]\n|term_start   = 5 November 2011\n|term_end     = 14 November 2015\n|predecessor  = [[Margaret Ritchie (politician)|Margaret Ritchie]]\n|successor    = [[Colum Eastwood]]\n|office1      = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Belfast South (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast South]]\n|term_start1  = 5 May 2005\n|term_end1    = 3 May 2017 \n|predecessor1 = [[Martin Smyth]]\n|successor1   = [[Emma Little-Pengelly]]\n|office2      = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]]<br />for [[Belfast South (Assembly constituency)|Belfast South]]\n|term_start2  = 25 June 1998\n|term_end2    = 21 June 2015\n|predecessor2 = Constituency established\n|successor2   = [[Claire Hanna (politician)|Claire Hanna]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1949|9|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Cushendall]], [[County Antrim]], [[Northern Ireland]]\n|death_date   = \n|party        = [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]]\n|spouse       = Olivia Nugent\n|children     = 4\n|alma_mater   = [[University College Dublin]]\n|website      = {{url|alasdairmcdonnell.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Alasdair McDonnell''' (born 1 September 1949) is an Irish politician who is a member of the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] (SDLP), and was its leader from 2011 to 2015. He was the Member of Parliament for [[Belfast South (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast South]] from 2005 to 2017.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url= http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/video-news/video-sdlps-dr-alasdair-mcdonnell-loses-south-belfast-seat-35808197.html|title= Video: SDLP's Dr Alasdair McDonnell loses South Belfast seat|work= [[Belfast Telegraph]]|author= Grattan, Gary|date= 9 June 2017|access-date= 9 June 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180117190543/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/video-news/video-sdlps-dr-alasdair-mcdonnell-loses-south-belfast-seat-35808197.html|archive-date= 17 January 2018|url-status= live}}</ref> and also a [[Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] of Northern Ireland for [[Belfast South (Assembly constituency)|Belfast South]] from 1998 to 2015.<ref name=RTE1>[http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1105/sdlp.html \"Alasdair McDonnell elected SDLP leader\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106124346/http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1105/sdlp.html |date=6 November 2011 }}, rte.ie, 5 November 2011.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n{{BLP sources section|date=May 2016}}\nMcDonnell's first involvement with [[Politics of Northern Ireland|politics]] came when he joined the [[National Democrats (Northern Ireland)|National Democrats]] and stood as the [[Parliamentary candidate|party candidate]] in the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 election]] in [[North Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|North Antrim]] and lost to [[Ian Paisley]].<ref>[http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/dna.htm North Antrim 1950\u20131970] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504050726/http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/dna.htm |date=4 May 2009 }}, ARK.ac.uk; accessed 15 May 2016.</ref>\n\nMcDonnell first won election to [[Belfast City Council]] in [[1977 Northern Ireland local elections|1977]], representing Belfast \"Area A\" which included the [[Short Strand]] and [[Ormeau Road|Upper Ormeau]] areas. He lost his council seat in a surprise result in [[1981 Northern Ireland local elections|1981]] but returned in [[1985 Northern Ireland local elections|1985]] and served as the first Catholic [[Mayor of Belfast|Deputy Mayor of Belfast]] in 1995\u201396.\n\nHe first stood for the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Westminster]] [[Belfast South (UK Parliament constituency)|constituency of South Belfast]] in the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 general election]] and subsequently contested the constituency at each subsequent general election, though not in the 1986 by-election (caused by the resignation of [[Unionists (Ireland)|Unionist]] MPs in protest at the [[Anglo Irish Agreement]]). He was also elected from the constituency to the [[Northern Ireland Peace Forum]] in 1996 and the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] in [[1998 Northern Ireland Assembly election|1998]] and [[2003 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2003]].\n\nIn 2004 he became his party's deputy leader. In the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] McDonnell generated one of the most sensational results in Northern Ireland when he won South Belfast, primarily due to a split in the [[Unionists (Ireland)|unionist]] vote. He received 10,339 votes while the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] (DUP) candidate Jimmy Spratt received 9,104 votes and [[Ulster Unionist Party]] candidate [[Michael McGimpsey]] received 7,263 votes. He was then re-elected by an increased majority in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]]. On 5 November 2011, he was elected leader of the SDLP at its conference in Belfast, succeeding [[Margaret Ritchie (politician)|Margaret Ritchie]].<ref name=\"RTE1\"/>\n\nIn a 2012 interview with ''[[The News Letter]]'', McDonnell criticised [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. He said the party were run along \"Soviet style\" lines where there was a military structure and where former terrorists were being placed into positions of power. He also claimed many people voting for Sinn F\u00e9in were doing so as an act of defiance.<ref name=\"McBride\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/ni-news/co-tyrone/sdlp-scorn-for-soviet-style-sf-1-4138356|title=SDLP scorn for Soviet style SF|work=[[The News Letter]]|date=8 August 2012|accessdate=1 June 2015|author=McBride, Sam}}</ref>\n\nAs SDLP chief, McDonnell described the terms of the [[Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies]], a seemingly blocked plan to reduce the number of MPs in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] by 50 (including two from Northern Ireland) to 600, as \"a bureaucratic numbers game initiated by [[Conservative Party (UK)|the Tories]] for purely party political advantage\".<ref name=\"Clarke\">{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/politics/sdlp-chief-alasdair-mcdonnell-relishes-coalition-row-that-could-save-his-seat-28778816.html|title=SDLP chief Alasdair McDonnell relishes coalition row that could save his seat|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|date=8 August 2012|accessdate=1 June 2015|author=Clarke, Liam|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611003309/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/politics/sdlp-chief-alasdair-mcdonnell-relishes-coalition-row-that-could-save-his-seat-28778816.html|archive-date=11 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, the SDLP abstained during the vote on the Civil Service (Special Advisers) Bill<ref name=\"NIAssembly\">{{cite news|url=http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/assembly-business/legislation/current-non-executive-bill-proposals/civil-service-special-advisers-bill |title=NI Assembly Civil Service (Special Advisers) Bill |date=8 July 2013 |accessdate=8 April 2015 |work=NI Assembly |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413121628/http://www.niassembly.gov.uk/assembly-business/legislation/current-non-executive-bill-proposals/civil-service-special-advisers-bill/ |archivedate=13 April 2015 }}</ref> in [[Stormont, Belfast|Stormont]], ensuring its passing. This led to claims from [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] that the SDLP was endorsing a 'hierarchy of victims' agenda and abandoning the principles of the [[Good Friday Agreement]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-22759895|title=Special adviser bill passed after marathon Stormont debate|date=4 June 2013|accessdate=5 June 2013|work=[[BBC News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604014930/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-22759895|archive-date=4 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDespite the reported claims<ref name=\"BBC\"/> from Sinn F\u00e9in that it was inevitable that someone would mount a legal challenge to \"what republicans view as a discriminatory law\" no such challenge has since emerged. In the [[2015 United Kingdom general election]] he stood again in Belfast South and was returned on 24.5% of the vote, the lowest ever vote share recorded by a successful MP in any part of the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/ni-politics/mcdonnell-won-s-belfast-with-lowest-ever-vote-share-by-a-uk-mp-1-6735240|title=McDonnell won S. Belfast with lowest ever vote share by a UK MP|first=Ben|last=Lowry|work=[[The News Letter]]|date=9 May 2015|accessdate=24 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131003823/http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/ni-politics/mcdonnell-won-s-belfast-with-lowest-ever-vote-share-by-a-uk-mp-1-6735240|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 November 2015, McDonnell lost the leadership contest held at the SDLP's annual conference. His successor as leader of the party, [[Colum Eastwood]], won with 172 votes to the 133 that McDonnell received.<ref>{{cite web|title=SDLP leadership: Colum Eastwood wins contest against Alasdair McDonnell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-34822651|website=BBC News|accessdate=14 November 2015|date=14 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114234835/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-34822651|archive-date=14 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2017, McDonnell lost his South Belfast seat to [[Emma Little-Pengelly]] (DUP) in the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.alasdairmcdonnell.com/ Alasdair McDonnell official website]\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=dr-alasdair-mcdonnell/1596 |publicwhip=Alasdair_McDonnell |theywork=alasdair_mcdonnell}}\n*[http://www.stratagem-ni.com/politician_specific.aspx?dataid=357958 Profile]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, stratagem-ni.com\n*[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-9665,00.html Profile], Guardian.co.uk\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050615/debtext/50615-17.htm Maiden Speech: House of Commons \u2013 15 June 2005]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ian Adamson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord Mayor of Belfast|Deputy Lord Mayor of Belfast]]|years=1995\u20131996}}\n{{s-aft|after=Margaret Crooks}}\n\n{{s-par|ni/for}}\n{{s-new|forum}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Northern Ireland Forum]]<br />[[South Belfast (Assembly constituency)|South Belfast]]|years=1996\u20131998}}\n{{s-non|reason=Forum dissolved}}\n\n{{s-par|ni/ass}}\n{{s-new|Assembly }}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]]<br />for [[Belfast South (Assembly constituency)|Belfast South]]|years=1998\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Claire Hanna (politician)|Claire Hanna]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Martin Smyth]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Belfast South (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast South]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emma Little-Pengelly]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Margaret Ritchie (politician)|Margaret Ritchie]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Colum Eastwood]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Social Democratic and Labour Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McDonnell, Alasdair}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of Belfast City Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Belfast constituencies (since 1922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Northern Ireland Forum]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Party (Northern Ireland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 1998\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2003\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2007\u20132011]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2011\u20132016]]\n[[Category:People from Cushendall]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic and Labour Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic and Labour Party MPs (UK)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "Punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alasdair_McDonnell"}
{"title_page": "Tom Rees (rugby union)", "text_new": "{{other people||Thomas Rees (disambiguation)}}\n{{For|the rugby union and rugby league footballer of the 1920s and 1930s for Wales (RU), Pontyclun, Crawshays, Army XV, London Welsh, Great Britain (RL), Oldham, and Broughton Rangers|Tommy Rees (disambiguation){{!}}Thomas Rees}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2009}}\n{{infobox rugby biography\n| name           = Tom Rees\n| image          = https://sm.imgix.net/11/34/tomrees_londonwasps_20101121.jpg?w=640&h=480&auto=compress,format&fit=clip\n| image_size     = 300 x 225\n| caption        = Tom Rees\n| alt            = \n| birth_name     = Thomas Rees\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1984|9|11}}\n| birth_place    = London, England\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{convert|1.83|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|102|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.premiershiprugby.com/premiership/rugby/london_wasps.php?section=1 |title= Aviva Premiership Rugby \u2013 London Wasps |work= web page |publisher= Premier Rugby |accessdate= 10 September 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120616063752/http://www.premiershiprugby.com/premiership/rugby/london_wasps.php?section=1 |archivedate= 16 June 2012 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n| school         = Harriet Costello Comprehensive School<br />[[RGS High Wycombe]]\n| university     = \n| spouse         = \n| children       = \n| relatives      = \n| occupation     = \n| ru_currentteam         = [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]]\n| ru_position            = [[Flanker (rugby union)|Flanker]]\n| ru_youthyears          = 1997\u20132000\n| ru_youthclubs          = [[Basingstoke R.F.C.|Basingstoke RFC]]\n| ru_clubyears           = 2004\u2013\n| ru_proclubs            = [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]]\n| ru_clubcaps            = 63{{0}}\n| ru_clubpoints          = 63{{0}}(60)\n| ru_clubupdate          = \n| ru_provinceyears       = \n| ru_province            = \n| ru_provincecaps        = \n| ru_provincepoints      = \n| super14years           = &nbsp;\n| super14                = \n| super14caps            = \n| super14points          = \n| ru_nationalyears       = 2006\u2013<br />2007\u20132008\n| ru_nationalteam        = [[England Saxons|England A]]<br />[[England national rugby union team|England]]\n| ru_nationalcaps        = <br />15{{0}}\n| ru_nationalpoints      = <br />15{{0}}(5)\n| ru_ntupdate            = 29 November 2008\n| ru_sevensnationalyears = &nbsp;\n| ru_sevensnationalteam  = \n| ru_sevensnationalcomp  = \n| ru_coachyears          = \n| ru_coachclubs          = \n| ru_refereeyears        = \n| ru_refereecomps        = \n| ru_refereeapps         = \n}}\n\n'''Thomas Rees''' (born 11 September 1984) is an ex-[[rugby union]] footballer who played [[Flanker (rugby union)|flanker]] for [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]] and has represented England at senior, Under-21, Under-19, Under-18 and Under-16 levels as well as [[England national rugby sevens team|sevens]]. He announced his retirement due to persistent injuries on 10 March 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scrum.com/premiership/rugby/player/15445.html |title=Tom Rees |accessdate=1 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nBorn 11 September 1984 in London, Rees began playing rugby at Harriet Costello Secondary School (now [[The Costello School]]) in 1996. He also joined the youth team at [[Basingstoke R.F.C.|Basingstoke RFC]] the following year. Under the guidance of Andy Bloodworth (of Chineham RFC) and Dave Luff, Rees progressed in the sport, initially playing in the [[Rugby union positions#13. Outside centre .26 12. Inside centre|centre]] before eventually specialising at openside flanker. Rees was eventually selected for England U16s, where he was awarded player of the year, and which led to his receiving offers from many Rugby-playing grammar schools: he chose to attend [[Royal Grammar School, High Wycombe|The Royal Grammar School]] in High Wycombe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scrum.com/premiership/rugby/player/15445.html|title=Tom Rees|accessdate=1 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rees: I want to follow in old boys' footsteps|url=http://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/sport/576106.0/|publisher=[[Bucks Free Press]]|date=4 March 2005}}</ref> Rees went on to play for England U18s and then U19s, being the first-choice openside flanker in both sides. He then signed for London Wasps on an academy contract, and after two years and having just broken into the first team, he was offered a first team contract, which he re-signed on a two-year deal.\n\nWith Wasps he won both the [[Heineken Cup]] in 2007<ref name=\"Heineken Cup final: Leicester 9-25 Wasps\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6663245.stm|title=Heineken Cup final: Leicester 9\u201325 Wasps|publisher=BBC|date=19 May 2007|accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref> and the 2008 [[Guinness Premiership]] title, scoring a try in the latter final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/7426519.stm |title=Guinness Premiership final |publisher=BBC|date=31 May 2008 |accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe returned to action on 27 March 2010 against Northampton, which ended 14 9 to Northampton but this followed wins over Gloucester, Worcester and London Irish.\n\nOn 10 March 2012, Rees was forced to retire from Rugby on the advice he received after sustaining a knee injury.\n\nRees is currently a doctor at Basingstoke hospital.\n\n==Representative career==\n\nRees captained the England U21 side in the [[Rugby Union Six Nations Championship|Six Nations Championship]] but was not selected for the elite England squad for the 2005 autumn internationals due to a knee injury sustained during the 2005 [[Zurich Premiership]] semi-finals.\n\nRees represented [[England Saxons|England A]] against [[Ireland A national rugby union team|Ireland A]] in early 2006.<ref name=\"England A 18-33 Ireland A \">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/international/4818966.stm|title=England A 18\u201333 Ireland A |publisher=BBC|date=17 March 2006|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nRees had a string of injuries during the [[2005\u201306 Guinness Premiership|2005\u201306 season]], but on his return put in strong performances at Wasps and was granted his place in the full England squad after representing England at all age groups possible.\n\nRees made his full [[England national rugby union team|England]] debut on 3 February 2007 against [[Scotland Rugby Union Team|Scotland]], coming on as a substitute for [[Joe Worsley]].<ref name=\"England 42-20 Scotland\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6320339.stm|title=England 42\u201320 Scotland|publisher=BBC|date=3 February 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Rees started his first game in the 26\u201318 victory against [[France national rugby union team|France]] on 11 March 2007 and was awarded the RBS Man of The Match Award by [[Brian Moore (rugby union)|Brian Moore]].<ref name=\"England 26-18 France\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6438439.stm|title=England 26\u201318 France|publisher=BBC|date=3 February 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Rees also started the next game against [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]].<ref name=\"Wales 27-18 England\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6454287.stm|title=Wales 27\u201318 England|publisher=BBC|date=17 March 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nRees made his [[Rugby World Cup|World Cup]] debut in England's initial group game against [[United States national rugby union team|USA]].<ref name=\"England 28-10 USA\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/6983423.stm|title=England 28\u201310 USA |publisher=BBC|date=8 September 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Despite England under performing Rees was signalled out along with back [[Olly Barkley]] as two positives from the victory. Rees' second half try in that game put him second behind [[Nigel Redman]] as England's youngest try scoring forward during a World Cup Finals event. Despite starting in the following game against [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]]<ref name=\"England 0-36 South Africa\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/6994767.stm|title=England 0\u201336 South Africa|publisher=BBC|date=14 September 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Rees failed to make another appearance during the [[2007 Rugby World Cup|2007 World Cup]]. A thigh injury kept him out of the matches against [[Tonga national rugby union team|Tonga]] and [[Samoa national rugby union team|Samoa]] and during this time [[Lewis Moody]] claimed the number 7 shirt for the remainder of the tournament.\n\nDespite a supposed lack of form for his club side London Wasps since his return from the World Cup, Rees made [[Brian Ashton (rugby union)|Brian Ashton's]] 32-man training squad for the [[2008 Six Nations]] and earned a place on the bench for the Six Nations opener against [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] ahead of other open-side specialists [[Michael Lipman]] and [[Magnus Lund]].<ref name=\"England 19-26 Wales\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/7215056.stm|title=England 19\u201326 Wales|publisher=BBC|date=2 February 2008|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nRees' strong form towards the end of the [[2007\u201308 Guinness Premiership]] saw him selected to travel to New Zealand to represent England in a two-test summer tour. He was then selected to start the first test at number 7 on 14 June 2008, a game which England lost 37\u201320.<ref name=\"New Zealand 37-20 England\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/7449881.stm|title=New Zealand 37\u201320 England|publisher=BBC|date=14 June 2008|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Despite England's defeat, Rees had put in a decent performance{{Clarify|date=October 2013}} in that match. Rees was picked to start the second test in Christchurch on 21 June 2008. England were thumped 44\u201312;<ref name=\"New Zealand 44-12 England\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/7463686.stm|title=New Zealand 44\u201312 England|publisher=BBC|date=21 June 2008|accessdate=2 August 2009}}</ref> however, Rees again put in a performance he could be proud of{{Clarify|date=October 2013}} against the standout openside in world rugby, Richie McCaw. If Rees' career had not been cut short, he exhibited the potential to make the No.7 shirt his own. There is no doubt the England management would have been compelled to recognise Tom's natural ability as a player and a leader, enhancing the national team's strength and solving the No.7 debate.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.guinnesspremiership.com/stats/profiles.php?player=4978&includeref=dynamic Guinness Premiership profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110605081831/http://www.wasps.co.uk/playerdisplaySS.ink?skip=21&season=07%2F08&seasonl=2007%2F2008&playertype=P Wasps profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070822061210/http://www.england-rugby.com/englandrugby/index.cfm?fuseaction=News.News_Detail&storyid=15061 England profile]\n* [http://www.sporting-heroes.net/rugby-heroes/displayhero.asp?HeroID=7263 Tom Rees photo by sportingheroes.net]\n* [http://www.maximuscle.com/tom Tom Rees Video \u2013 Maximuscle Ambassador]\n\n{{England Squad 2007 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rees, Tom}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Wasps RFC players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union flankers]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Royal Grammar School, High Wycombe]]\n[[Category:Rugby union players from London]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Thomas Rees (disambiguation)}}\n{{For|the rugby union and rugby league footballer of the 1920s and 1930s for Wales (RU), Pontyclun, Crawshays, Army XV, London Welsh, Great Britain (RL), Oldham, and Broughton Rangers|Tommy Rees (disambiguation){{!}}Thomas Rees}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2009}}\n{{infobox rugby biography\n| name           = Tom Rees\n| image          = https://sm.imgix.net/11/34/tomrees_londonwasps_20101121.jpg?w=640&h=480&auto=compress,format&fit=clip\n| image_size     = 300 x 225\n| caption        = Tom Rees\n| alt            = \n| birth_name     = Thomas Rees\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1984|9|11}}\n| birth_place    = London, England\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{convert|1.83|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|102|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.premiershiprugby.com/premiership/rugby/london_wasps.php?section=1 |title= Aviva Premiership Rugby \u2013 London Wasps |work= web page |publisher= Premier Rugby |accessdate= 10 September 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120616063752/http://www.premiershiprugby.com/premiership/rugby/london_wasps.php?section=1 |archivedate= 16 June 2012 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n| school         = Harriet Costello Comprehensive School<br />[[RGS High Wycombe]]\n| university     = \n| spouse         = \n| children       = \n| relatives      = \n| occupation     = \n| ru_currentteam         = [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]]\n| ru_position            = [[Flanker (rugby union)|Flanker]]\n| ru_youthyears          = 1997\u20132000\n| ru_youthclubs          = [[Basingstoke R.F.C.|Basingstoke RFC]]\n| ru_clubyears           = 2004\u2013\n| ru_proclubs            = [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]]\n| ru_clubcaps            = 63{{0}}\n| ru_clubpoints          = 63{{0}}(60)\n| ru_clubupdate          = \n| ru_provinceyears       = \n| ru_province            = \n| ru_provincecaps        = \n| ru_provincepoints      = \n| super14years           = &nbsp;\n| super14                = \n| super14caps            = \n| super14points          = \n| ru_nationalyears       = 2006\u2013<br />2007\u20132008\n| ru_nationalteam        = [[England Saxons|England A]]<br />[[England national rugby union team|England]]\n| ru_nationalcaps        = <br />15{{0}}\n| ru_nationalpoints      = <br />15{{0}}(5)\n| ru_ntupdate            = 29 November 2008\n| ru_sevensnationalyears = &nbsp;\n| ru_sevensnationalteam  = \n| ru_sevensnationalcomp  = \n| ru_coachyears          = \n| ru_coachclubs          = \n| ru_refereeyears        = \n| ru_refereecomps        = \n| ru_refereeapps         = \n}}\n\n'''Thomas Rees''' (born 11 September 1984) is an ex-[[rugby union]] footballer who played [[Flanker (rugby union)|flanker]] for [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]] and has represented England at senior, Under-21, Under-19, Under-18 and Under-16 levels as well as [[England national rugby sevens team|sevens]]. He announced his retirement due to persistent injuries on 10 March 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scrum.com/premiership/rugby/player/15445.html |title=Tom Rees |accessdate=1 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nBorn 11 September 1984 in London, Rees began playing rugby at Harriet Costello Secondary School (now [[The Costello School]]) in 1996. He also joined the youth team at [[Basingstoke R.F.C.|Basingstoke RFC]] the following year. Under the guidance of Andy Bloodworth (of Chineham RFC) and Dave Luff, Rees progressed in the sport, initially playing in the [[Rugby union positions#13. Outside centre .26 12. Inside centre|centre]] before eventually specialising at openside flanker. Rees was eventually selected for England U16s, where he was awarded player of the year, and which led to his receiving offers from many Rugby-playing grammar schools: he chose to attend [[Royal Grammar School, High Wycombe|The Royal Grammar School]] in High Wycombe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scrum.com/premiership/rugby/player/15445.html|title=Tom Rees|accessdate=1 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rees: I want to follow in old boys' footsteps|url=http://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/sport/576106.0/|publisher=[[Bucks Free Press]]|date=4 March 2005}}</ref> Rees went on to play for England U18s and then U19s, being the first-choice openside flanker in both sides. He then signed for London Wasps on an academy contract, and after two years and having just broken into the first team, he was offered a first team contract, which he re-signed on a two-year deal.\n\nWith Wasps he won both the [[Heineken Cup]] in 2007<ref name=\"Heineken Cup final: Leicester 9-25 Wasps\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6663245.stm|title=Heineken Cup final: Leicester 9\u201325 Wasps|publisher=BBC|date=19 May 2007|accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref> and the 2008 [[Guinness Premiership]] title, scoring a try in the latter final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/7426519.stm |title=Guinness Premiership final |publisher=BBC|date=31 May 2008 |accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe returned to action on 27 March 2010 against Northampton, which ended 14 9 to Northampton but this followed wins over Gloucester, Worcester and London Irish.\n\nOn 10 March 2012, Rees was forced to retire from Rugby on the advice he received after sustaining a knee injury.\n\nRees is currently a doctor at Basingstoke hospital.\n\n==Representative career==\n\nRees captained the England U21 side in the [[Rugby Union Six Nations Championship|Six Nations Championship]] but was not selected for the elite England squad for the 2005 autumn internationals due to a knee injury sustained during the 2005 [[Zurich Premiership]] semi-finals.\n\nRees represented [[England Saxons|England A]] against [[Ireland A national rugby union team|Ireland A]] in early 2006.<ref name=\"England A 18-33 Ireland A \">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/international/4818966.stm|title=England A 18\u201333 Ireland A |publisher=BBC|date=17 March 2006|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nRees had a string of injuries during the [[2005\u201306 Guinness Premiership|2005\u201306 season]], but on his return put in strong performances at Wasps and was granted his place in the full England squad after representing England at all age groups possible.\n\nRees made his full [[England national rugby union team|England]] debut on 3 February 2007 against [[Scotland Rugby Union Team|Scotland]], coming on as a substitute for [[Joe Worsley]].<ref name=\"England 42-20 Scotland\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6320339.stm|title=England 42\u201320 Scotland|publisher=BBC|date=3 February 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Rees started his first game in the 26\u201318 victory against [[France national rugby union team|France]] on 11 March 2007 and was awarded the RBS Man of The Match Award by [[Brian Moore (rugby union)|Brian Moore]].<ref name=\"England 26-18 France\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6438439.stm|title=England 26\u201318 France|publisher=BBC|date=3 February 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Rees also started the next game against [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]].<ref name=\"Wales 27-18 England\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6454287.stm|title=Wales 27\u201318 England|publisher=BBC|date=17 March 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nRees made his [[Rugby World Cup|World Cup]] debut in England's initial group game against [[United States national rugby union team|USA]].<ref name=\"England 28-10 USA\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/6983423.stm|title=England 28\u201310 USA |publisher=BBC|date=8 September 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Despite England under performing Rees was signalled out along with back [[Olly Barkley]] as two positives from the victory. Rees' second half try in that game put him second behind [[Nigel Redman]] as England's youngest try scoring forward during a World Cup Finals event. Despite starting in the following game against [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]]<ref name=\"England 0-36 South Africa\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/6994767.stm|title=England 0\u201336 South Africa|publisher=BBC|date=14 September 2007|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Rees failed to make another appearance during the [[2007 Rugby World Cup|2007 World Cup]]. A thigh injury kept him out of the matches against [[Tonga national rugby union team|Tonga]] and [[Samoa national rugby union team|Samoa]] and during this time [[Lewis Moody]] claimed the number 7 shirt for the remainder of the tournament.\n\nDespite a supposed lack of form for his club side London Wasps since his return from the World Cup, Rees made [[Brian Ashton (rugby union)|Brian Ashton's]] 32-man training squad for the [[2008 Six Nations]] and earned a place on the bench for the Six Nations opener against [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] ahead of other open-side specialists [[Michael Lipman]] and [[Magnus Lund]].<ref name=\"England 19-26 Wales\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/7215056.stm|title=England 19\u201326 Wales|publisher=BBC|date=2 February 2008|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nRees' strong form towards the end of the [[2007\u201308 Guinness Premiership]] saw him selected to travel to New Zealand to represent England in a two-test summer tour. He was then selected to start the first test at number 7 on 14 June 2008, a game which England lost 37\u201320.<ref name=\"New Zealand 37-20 England\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/7449881.stm|title=New Zealand 37\u201320 England|publisher=BBC|date=14 June 2008|accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref> Despite England's defeat, Rees had put in a decent performance{{Clarify|date=October 2013}} in that match. Rees was picked to start the second test in Christchurch on 21 June 2008. England were thumped 44\u201312;<ref name=\"New Zealand 44-12 England\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/7463686.stm|title=New Zealand 44\u201312 England|publisher=BBC|date=21 June 2008|accessdate=2 August 2009}}</ref> however, Rees again put in a performance he could be proud of{{Clarify|date=October 2013}} against the standout openside in world rugby, Richie McCaw. If Rees' career had not been cut short, he exhibited the potential to make the No.7 shirt his own. There is no doubt the England management would have been compelled to recognise Tom's natural ability as a player and a leader, enhancing the national teams strength and solving the No.7 debate.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.guinnesspremiership.com/stats/profiles.php?player=4978&includeref=dynamic Guinness Premiership profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110605081831/http://www.wasps.co.uk/playerdisplaySS.ink?skip=21&season=07%2F08&seasonl=2007%2F2008&playertype=P Wasps profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070822061210/http://www.england-rugby.com/englandrugby/index.cfm?fuseaction=News.News_Detail&storyid=15061 England profile]\n* [http://www.sporting-heroes.net/rugby-heroes/displayhero.asp?HeroID=7263 Tom Rees photo by sportingheroes.net]\n* [http://www.maximuscle.com/tom Tom Rees Video \u2013 Maximuscle Ambassador]\n\n{{England Squad 2007 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rees, Tom}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Wasps RFC players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union flankers]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Royal Grammar School, High Wycombe]]\n[[Category:Rugby union players from London]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRepresentative career:Typo fixing, replaced: teams strength \u2192 team's strength", "url_page"