07/10/bc.cyc.tourdefrance.the.ap/index.html |title=Ex-Tour champ Thevenet defends his doping past |publisher=CNN }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1976 || [[Lucien Van Impe]] || Never failed tests ||\n|-\n| 1969\u20131972<br />1974 || [[Eddy Merckx]] || {{no|Failed tests}} || Merckx has failed tests three times, but never at the Tour de France. He was expelled from the 1969 Giro d'Italia after testing positive for Reactivan.<ref name=\"L'\u00c9quipe 13 March 2007\">L'\u00c9quipe, France, 13 March 2007</ref><br />\nHe failed tests for Mucantil after winning the 1973 Giro di Lombardia. The drug was later taken off the banned list.<ref name=\"L'\u00c9quipe 13 March 2007\" /> <br />\nIn the 1977 Fl\u00e8che Wallonne, Merckx failed tests for Stimul (pemoline), along with Freddy Maertens and Michel Pollentier .<ref>La Derni\u00e8re Heure (Brussels) 14 December 2003</ref>\n|-\n| 1973 || [[Luis Oca\u00f1a]] || {{no|Failed tests}} || Failed tests in the 1977 Tour de France (pemoline) 18th stage.\n|-\n| 1968 || [[Jan Janssen]] || Never failed tests ||\n|-\n| 1967 || [[Roger Pingeon]] || Never failed tests ||\n|-\n| 1966 || [[Lucien Aimar]] || {{no|Failed tests<br />Banned for one month}} || Missed the 1969 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a due to a one-month doping ban.\n|-\n| 1965 || [[Felice Gimondi]] || {{no|Failed tests}} || Failed tests in the 1968 Giro and 1975 Tour.\n|-\n| 1957<br />1961\u20131964 || [[Jacques Anquetil]] || Never failed tests {{no|Confessed doping use}} || Debated with French government minister on television, saying \"Leave me in peace; everybody takes dope.\" <br />After winning Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge in 1966, was temporarily disqualified after refusing a drug test, saying he had already been to the toilet. He was later reinstated after he engaged a lawyer as the case was never heard.\n|}\n\n== Doping histories of Top-10 finishers, 1998\u20132015 ==\n\nAn overview of the top 10 finishers in the [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]] in the [[Tour de France]] since 1998, along with their individual doping records.\n\nRiders' finishing positions are color-coded according to doping status, as explained in the legend below. Note that no distinction is made on whether a rider was doped before, during or after the particular race for which his name is listed, except if the rider was officially disqualified, such as [[Alberto Contador]], [[Bernhard Kohl]] and [[Floyd Landis]]. Except in these circumstances, the color code for a rider is the same in all years, and does not imply or allege that the rider was doped during any particular edition of the Tour.\n\n'''Legend :'''<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|style=\"background:black;color:white\"|Stripped of result in the current race due to doping.\n|-\n|style=\"background:red\"|Failed tests and/or sanctioned for doping in another competition or out of competition at some point in their career.\n|-\n|style=\"background:orange;\"|Admitted to doping without failed tests and/or sanction during career.\n|-\n|style=\"background:lime;\"|Failed tests for doping but later acquitted.\n|-\n|style=\"background:silver;\"|Accused of doping without failed tests, sanction or admittance in their career.\n|-\n|style=\"background:white;\"|Has never been: stripped of a title, failed tests or sanctioned for doping to date, with no known accusations.\n|-\n|}\n\n=== 1998 Tour de France ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-bottom:0px;\"\n|-\n!Rank\n!Name\n!Team\n!Time\n!Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:red\"|  1 || [[Marco Pantani]] || Mercatone Uno || align=right nowrap| 92h 49' 46\" || Forced to take a two-week break from racing in 1999 Giro for irregular blood values.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pantani: Future 'in doubt' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/361640.stm |publisher=BBC  |date=5 June 1999 |accessdate=30 June 2011}}</ref> Implicated in the [[Operaci\u00f3n Puerto doping case]] in 2006. Died of a cocaine overdose in 2004.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:red\"|  2 || [[Jan Ullrich]] || Telekom || align=right| +3' 21\" || Implicated in Telekom affair and [[Operaci\u00f3n Puerto]]. Banned retroactively in 2011 for the period 2005-07.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jan Ullrich given two-year ban from CAS |work=Cyclingnews |publisher=Immediate Media Company |date=9 February 2012 |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/jan-ullrich-given-two-year-ban-from-cas  |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:orange;\"|  3 || [[Bobby Julich]] || Cofidis || align=right| +4' 08\" || Accused of doping by teammate [[Philippe Gaumont]] in the book ''Prisonnier du dopage''. Admitted to doping in October 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: Bobby Julich doping confession |publisher=CyclingNews |date=25 October 2012 |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/exclusive-bobby-julich-doping-confession |accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Julich leaves Team Sky |publisher=Team Sky Pro Cycling |date=25 October 2012 |url=http://www.teamsky.com/article/0,27290,17553_8194069,00.html |accessdate=25 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028144514/http://www.teamsky.com/article/0%2C27290%2C17553_8194069%2C00.html |archivedate=28 October 2012  }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:silver;\"|  4 || [[Christophe Rinero]] || Cofidis || align=right| +9' 16\" || Accused of doping by teammate [[Philippe Gaumont]] in the book ''Prisonnier du dopage''.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:red\"|  5 || [[Michael Boogerd]] || Rabobank || align=right| +11' 26\"\n|| Accused by Floyd Landis of blood doping.<ref>{{cite news |title=Michael Boogerd responds to Floyd Landis accusations |work=Velonation |publisher=velonation |date=1 February 2011 |url= http://www.velonation.com/News/ID/7281/Michael-Boogerd-responds-to-Floyd-Landis-accusations.aspx |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> A